<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stars' Hatcher Suspended 7 Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The NHL suspended Dallas Stars defenseman Derian  
Hatcher for seven games on Saturday, for leaving his feet to hit 
Phoenix Coyotes center Jeremy Roenick and inflicting a multiple jaw 
fracture on April 14. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatcher served his first game during Saturday's 2-0 loss to  
Phoenix and will miss Sunday's game against the Avalanche in 
Colorado, as well as the Stars' first five playoff games. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatcher's suspension is the longest in playoff history since  
Maurice (Rocket) Richard was suspended, after punching a linesmen 
in March 1955, for the final three games of the regular season and 
the entire playoffs. New York Rangers center Adam Graves was 
suspended for four games in the 1992 playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is clear that Mr. Hatcher intended to deliver a blow to the  
head of Mr. Roenick by leaving his feet immediately prior to the 
hit,'' said Colin Campbell, the NHL's director of hockey 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``As well, the severity of the injury to Mr. Roenick was  
considered as was the fact that Mr. Hatcher has been suspended by 
the league on previous occasions, most recently last September.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hatcher was suspended for four games in September for  
cross-checking St. Louis Blues' defenseman Chris Pronger. Hatcher 
will forfeit $90,731 of his salary to the NHL players' emergency 
fund. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very severe penalty,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said  
after his team's 2-0 loss Saturday at Phoenix. ``Both teams suffer. 
We're missing our captain, our leader, one of our best players. 
Derian has to take responsibility for what he did. And we're going 
to have to work through it in the playoffs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roenick was discharged from the hospital Saturday and met with  
reporters during the game, although his jaw was badly swollen and 
his broken right thumb bandaged from a slash by Stars defenseman 
Craig Ludwig right before Hatcher's hit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hate to say what's fair or unfair,'' Roenick said about  
Hatcher's suspension. ``My opinion is I can't play in the playoffs, 
so I don't see why he should get to play in the playoffs. That's 
why I hope they get knocked out in the first round.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
