<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Work Begins for Oklahoma City Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- The peaceful, grassy lawn has been ripped  
away, replaced by raw dirt and construction machines as crews begin 
building a permanent memorial park on the site where a bomb killed 
168 people in the Murrah Federal Building. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, relatives of some of the victims will gather to  
observe the fourth anniversary of the disaster, their last such 
observance before the park is completed next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Visitors ``can begin to see what it's going to become and how  
powerful it's going to become,'' said Kari Ferguson, spokeswoman 
for the Oklahoma City National Memorial Foundation. ``I think it 
will forever draw people from around the world who want to learn 
more about that moment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rob Kaufman visited last week, coming all the way from San  
Antonio, and said it wouldn't his last trip. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll come back and see it, see what the actual memorial is  
like,'' he said quietly. 
</P>
<P>
	The project is on schedule and on budget, and should be finished  
in time for the fifth anniversary on April 19, 2000, organizers 
say. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our mission is to make sure they never forget,'' said Ms.  
Ferguson. ``We don't need to forget the lessons we learned that day 
or the lessons we've learned every day since.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A huge truck bomb blew up at 9:02 a.m. on April 19, 1995, at the  
curb right outside the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building. A third 
of the nine-story building was blown away or collapsed into a pile 
of rubble. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, what was left of the building was torn down, and the lawn  
was planted to cover the scars until the permanent memorial could 
take its place. 
</P>
<P>
	A chain-link fence surrounding the site became a spontaneous  
memorial as visitors tied on mementos: baseball caps, key chain 
charms, hair ribbons, bracelets, small children's toys -- often just 
any object they happened to have at hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``They leave their memories to be a part of it, and I guess  
that's what makes it special,'' said Stuart Earnest, who lives a 
block from the site and lost friends in the blast. ``People who 
don't have a clue share their emotions and sympathy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Volunteers periodically collect the offerings, which become part  
of a growing archive of artifacts from the bombing. Ms. Ferguson 
said about 40,000 items have been removed. 
</P>
<P>
	The fence has been moved back to make room for the construction,  
and sections of it were emptied of mementos again last week to make 
room for new offerings on Monday's anniversary. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Ferguson said about $19.7 million of the estimated $29.1  
million cost of the memorial has been raised. The money will pay 
for the park, a museum that is projected to open in 2000, and 
offices for the Memorial Institute for the Prevention of Terrorism. 
</P>
<P>
	A feature of the park will be the Survivor Tree, an elm that  
survived the blast and has become a symbol to survivors. To protect 
its extensive root system from the construction, volunteers 
hand-dug 100 holes for concrete piers that will support an elevated 
deck and walkway around the tree. 
</P>
<P>
	A forester also is working with construction workers.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's the best-taken care of tree in the world, I promise,''  
Ms. Ferguson said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
