<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 08:52:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Offers Elder Protection Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton outlined proposals today to  
``investigate, prosecute and punish'' people who abuse older 
Americans in nursing homes and to deny telephone service to 
telemarketers who prey on the elderly. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposals, which go to Congress next month, also target  
people who defraud health care plans at an annual cost to taxpayers 
of billions of dollars. The president is pushing tougher penalties 
for those who steal from pensions and retirement funds. 
</P>
<P>
	In his weekly radio address, Clinton said violent crime is at  
its lowest level in 25 years, and ``for elderly Americans who once 
locked themselves into their homes in fear, the falling crime rate 
is a godsend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, however, ``the greatest threat that many older Americans  
face is not a criminal armed with a gun but a telemarketer armed 
with a deceptive rap. And our most defenseless seniors, those who 
are sick or disabled and living in nursing homes, cannot lock the 
door against abuse and neglect by people paid to care for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Telemarketers bilk Americans of an estimated $40 billion a year,  
Clinton said, and more than half the victims of are over 50 years 
old. ``That's like a fraud tax aimed directly at senior citizens,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He wants to give the Justice Department authority to seek a  
court order to withdraw telephone service from any number proved to 
have been used in telemarketing fraud. Federal law now permits 
numbers to be blocked only when they are used for illegal gambling. 
</P>
<P>
	As for care of the elderly, the president is proposing prison  
sentences of up to 10 years for individuals and fines for nursing 
home chains of up to $2 million for each home where residents are 
neglected or abused. No federal criminal penalties now exist for 
such activities. 
</P>
<P>
	``When one out of four nursing homes in America does not provide  
quality care to their residents, and when people living in 
substandard nursing homes have as much fear from abuse and neglect 
as they do from the diseases of old age, we must do more,'' Clinton 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	His proposal permits the Justice Department to seek court orders  
to stop nursing homes from mistreating patients. The plan also 
protects whistle-blowers who tell officials about wrongdoing in 
nursing homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
