<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 17:32:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Knows How Gretzky Feels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- As the ambassador for the sport he still loves,  
Michael Jordan knows better than anyone what Wayne Gretzky is 
experiencing as ``The Great One'' gets ready to leave hockey. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad to see that he made the choice he felt comfortable  
with. A lot of people probably wanted to see him play but only he 
knows and I understand that truly,'' Jordan said Saturday night 
before he watched, of all things, a hockey game. 
</P>
<P>
	Three months after his retirement from basketball, Jordan  
visited his old Bulls locker room for the first time. He was at the 
United Center to be interviewed about Gretzky and later to watch 
Chris Chelios, the former Blackhawks captain, return to the United 
Center for the first time with the Detroit Red Wings. 
</P>
<P>
	In a brief but wide-ranging interview in the corridor, Jordan  
said he is still interested in purchasing part of the Charlotte 
Hornets, was not surprised that the Los Angeles Lakers released his 
former teammate Dennis Rodman and had no problem with someone using 
his old locker, which now sits empty. 
</P>
<P>
	He is an acquaintance and occasional golf partner of Gretzky.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure there are challenges out there and Wayne will find  
some of those in business or whatever opportunity you may find,'' 
Jordan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan said walking back into the locker room where he once  
dressed was not a traumatic experience. But he sounded 
philosophical. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got a lot of memories, but it's always a great pleasure to  
come back,'' he said 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately it was not to get dressed or anything to that  
nature. I'm here to watch a hockey game, but I mean that's where my 
life is going. I'm coming back to watch other things instead of 
play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan's old locker was boarded shut earlier in the season but  
now just sits empty. The team that still calls itself the Bulls 
struggles nearly every night just to score 70 points, a far cry 
from the one that won six NBA championships in the 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	``People can use it (the locker), I don't have a problem with  
that, it doesn't bother me,'' Jordan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's in the past. It's a whole new era and things are going to  
happen, things are going to change. They have to rebuild and get 
themselves back to the goal that we set. We set high standards and 
it's going to be a challenge for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan said he was aware that earlier this month the Bulls set  
an NBA record by scoring just 49 points, the lowest output since 
the inception of the shot clock in 1954. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was pretty ugly. I think I can do better than that,''  
said the man who scored at least 50 points in a game 38 times 
during his career. 
</P>
<P>
	On purchasing part of the Hornets, Jordan said:  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm still in conversation, still evaluating the opportunity.  
There is nothing that I can report at this time. There is some 
interest. It's only just from an economical standpoint and I will 
evaluate it. Until I feel like it's appropriate for me to make an 
announcement, I won't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers finally got fed up with Rodman's antics, being late  
for practices and pretty much living by his own set of rules -- as 
he often did while helping the Bulls win three titles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Very few people can deal with Dennis. We did a good job with  
that. I don't know if there's anybody else out there that can deal 
with him,'' Jordan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He carries a lot of baggage.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 14:12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smith Looks To Match Up With Couch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Sipe and Anderson. Bernie and Boomer. Couch  
and Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio's pro football rivalry has a new set of bookend  
quarterbacks, and the one headed to Cincinnati is looking forward 
to it with a little vengeance at heart. 
</P>
<P>
	When Cleveland decided to make Tim Couch the top pick in the NFL  
draft Saturday, Akili Smith went to the Cincinnati Bengals with the 
third choice and immediately talked about proving the Browns wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals passed up a tempting offer from New Orleans -- all of  
the Saints' picks this year, their No. 1 picks in 2000 and 2001 and 
a second-rounder in 2002 to trade down -- because they wanted Smith 
so badly. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have gone a long time here trying to solve our quarterback  
problem,'' general manager Mike Brown said. ``I am convinced that 
is our principle problem. We've got to get it resolved at some 
point on a satisfactory basis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith wasn't surprised that he wound up with Cincinnati and he  
wasn't happy at how the process unfolded. He had hoped to beat out 
Couch for the No. 1 pick and didn't like how the Browns handled the 
process -- he felt they used him as leverage in negotiations with 
Couch. 
</P>
<P>
	``We play those guys twice a year. That's going to motivate me a  
lot,'' Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	Just as Peyton Manning and Ryan Leaf were scrutinized  
side-by-side as rookies, Smith and Couch can expect attention that 
will be even more intense because of their cities' proximity. 
</P>
<P>
	``It should be a rivalry that's going to go on for a long time  
with them being in the same division and me and him battling for 
the No. 1 pick all the way through,'' Smith said. ``We're going to 
be competing for the rest of our lives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals hope so. After racking up twice as many losses as  
wins in the 1990s while going through 10 quarterbacks, Brown 
decided he had to pass on the Saints' offer to get passer No. 11. 
</P>
<P>
	The Saints, who chose 12th overall, called Brown on Saturday and  
made an offer so good that he fawned over it after rejecting it. 
</P>
<P>
	``They offered and they offered very generously,'' Brown said.  
``It was hard to turn down, but we did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no guarantee to get another quarterback at the No.  
12 spot and that was the big factor,'' coach Bruce Coslet said. 
``It was a very attractive deal. It was a hard decision to make.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saints coach Mike Ditka understood. The Saints eventually swung  
a deal with Washington to get running back Ricky Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know how people could have turned us down,'' Ditka  
said. ``But if you've got a guy you want, no deal's good enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They turned down a lot of picks for the future of the  
Cincinnati Bengals to get me,'' Smith said. ``So it becomes a 
burden on me to respond to something like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals went through four quarterbacks last season while  
finishing 3-13 for the fourth time in the '90s. Smith's arrival 
means that Neil O'Donnell's days with the Bengals are over. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown told O'Donnell he will be released as early as next week.  
Jeff Blake is the starter for now, but Smith hopes to displace him 
quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith doesn't lack confidence. He admires Randall Cunningham and  
John Elway and compared himself to them on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like Randall a lot because of his mobility and I like John  
Elway because his release is kind of like mine,'' Smith said. ``So 
I'd like to say you put John Elway's arm on Cunningham, that's kind 
of what you're getting in me.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
