<HEADLINE> Filling Needs at the NFL Draft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- How NFL teams filled their needs with their  
first selections in Saturday's draft: 
</P>
<P>
	1, CLEVELAND -- When you're starting a franchise, you look for a  
franchise quarterback. That's an NFL axiom the Browns heeded wisely 
by taking TIM COUCH, QB, KENTUCKY. Couch might sit behind Ty Detmer 
for his rookie year, but not long beyond that. 
</P>
<P>
	2, PHILADELPHIA -- A playmaker with the ability to get outside  
while operating behind a mediocre offensive line? Try DONOVAN 
McNABB, QB, SYRACUSE. The Eagles did, hoping to boost an offense 
that scored 161 points last year. 
</P>
<P>
	3, CINCINNATI -- The Bengals already had four quarterbacks on the  
roster, but weren't enamored of any of them. So AKILI SMITH, QB, 
OREGON, was the choice. He has the strongest arm of any passing 
prospect, and will have decent weapons to work with. 
</P>
<P>
	4, INDIANAPOLIS -- EDGERRIN JAMES, RB, MIAMI, FLA., isn't Ricky  
Williams. The Colts apparently believe he is a better receiver, and 
after dealing away Marshall Faulk, they need a running back who can 
catch the ball as an outlet for Peyton Manning. 
</P>
<P>
	But James had only one outstanding season in college. Williams  
is the NCAA Division I career rushing leader. 
</P>
<P>
	5, NEW ORLEANS -- Mike Ditka would have offered the Superdome for  
RICKY WILLIAMS, RB, TEXAS, if ``Da Coach'' owned it. Instead, he 
traded six picks this year and two next year with Washington to 
move up seven spots. That's an incredible price to pay for a guy 
Ditka compares with Walter Payton. He'd better be. 
</P>
<P>
	6, ST. LOUIS -- The Rams bolstered their draft when they traded  
for Marshall Faulk on Thursday. They further upgraded a dreary 
offense with TORRY HOLT, WR, NORTH CAROLINA STATE. Now if anyone 
can find Isaac Bruce. 
</P>
<P>
	7, WASHINGTON -- For a team in ownership limbo, the Redskins did  
a spectacular job. They gained seven picks over two years, and 
still wound up with the guy they wanted, CHAMP BAILEY, CB, GEORGIA. 
Washington is aging at cornerback and also occasionally can use 
Bailey at receiver. He'll run back kicks, too. A superb pick for 
what they need. 
</P>
<P>
	8, ARIZONA -- The Cardinals are building a nice offense and Jake  
Plummer will love throwing to DAVID BOSTON, WR, OHIO STATE. Boston 
also brings a bit of attitude to go with his skills getting open 
deep and should provide balance to Rob Moore and Frank Sanders. 
</P>
<P>
	9, DETROIT -- The Lions weren't expecting CHRIS CLAIBORNE, LB,  
SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA, to slip this far. The All-American, who can 
play inside and outside, should fill a need on the outside and 
start immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	10, BALTIMORE -- Even though they took a cornerback first last  
season (Duane Starks), the Ravens couldn't resist CHRIS McALISTER, 
CB, ARIZONA. He'll free aging Rod Woodson to move to safety and 
also will return kicks. Look for some big plays from McAlister 
right away. 
</P>
<P>
	11, MINNESOTA -- The Vikings really wanted McAlister after losing  
Corey Fuller as a free agent. Instead, in the Draft of the 
Quarterbacks, they opted to groom one behind Randall Cunningham. 
DAUNTE CULPEPPER, QB, CENTRAL FLORIDA, is a bit raw and untested on 
the highest level. But this team has time on its side. 
</P>
<P>
	12, CHICAGO -- The run on quarterbacks continued as the Bears  
went for CADE McNOWN, QB, UCLA. Very productive, even though he 
doesn't fit the prototype NFL quarterback, McNown could be the 
first of this crop to actually start as a pro. 
</P>
<P>
	13, PITTSBURGH -- A bit of reach here? TROY EDWARDS, WR, LOUSIANA  
TECH, was highly productive on a lower level and projected as a 
late first-rounder. But after allowing Yancey Thigpen and Charles 
Johnson to slip away as free agents, the Steelers were desperate 
enough to gamble. 
</P>
<P>
	14, KANSAS CITY -- For the second straight year, the Chiefs  
tended to their offensive line. JOHN TAIT, T, BYU, was the first 
blocker selected and could slide in opposite last year's No. 1, 
Victor Riley, who started as a rookie. 
</P>
<P>
	15, TAMPA BAY -- Warren Sapp must be smiling from ear to ear. By  
taking ANTHONY McFARLAND, DT, LSU, the Bucs solidified their 
defensive line and enhanced Sapp's impact. With none of the touted 
QBs available, Tampa decided to fill a minor need on defense with a 
top-rank player. 
</P>
<P>
	16, TENNESSEE -- The Titans wanted a defensive lineman or  
linebacker. They are especially weak at DE, and JEVON KEARSE, 
DE-LB, FLORIDA, fit nicely. Kearse is more likely to have an impact 
rushing the passer, a weakness in Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	17, NEW ENGLAND -- After losing Dave Wohlabaugh to free agency,  
the Patriots had a chasm at center. They filled it drafting DAMIEN 
WOODY, C, BOSTON COLLEGE, but why move up three spots in a trade 
for someone who probably would have been there at No. 20? 
</P>
<P>
	18, OAKLAND -- The defense has lots of needs, but another primary  
one was offensive tackle. MATT STINCHCOMB, T, GEORGIA, an 
All-American who needs to get stronger, but is smart and tenacious. 
Should be a starter in '99. 
</P>
<P>
	19, NEW YORK GIANTS -- The recent history of picks from Notre  
Dame has been spotty. The Giants, who have struggled with 
first-rounders (Dave Brown, Tyrone Wheatley, Thomas Lewis), really 
stretched for LUKE PETITGOUT, T, NOTRE DAME. They have a need at 
right tackle, where Petitgout plays, but some scouts projected him 
for the second round. 
</P>
<P>
	20, DALLAS -- With Leon Lett's status very shaky, the Cowboys  
opted to address the defensive line. In EBENEZER EKUBAN, DE, NORTH 
CAROLINA, they get a quick sackmaster who isn't the run-stopper 
Lett is, but can learn. Dallas moved up two spots to get him. 
</P>
<P>
	21, ARIZONA -- With speedy David Boston on hand, the Cardinals  
could look for bulk. A left tackle was the most pressing need, and 
they got L.J. SHELTON, T, EASTERN MICHIGAN. He'll get a chance to 
start right off. 
</P>
<P>
	22, SEATTLE -- After two trades downward, the Seahawks finally  
got going and bolstered their defensive line with LAMAR KING, DE, 
SAGINAW VALLEY. There's no major need here, but the wideouts and 
cornerbacks who were attractive already were gone. 
</P>
<P>
	23, BUFFALO -- One of the few totally expected picks in the round  
was ANTOINE WINFIELD, CB, OHIO STATE. A hard-hitter who is a bit 
small, Winfield easily could start, but certainly will work in the 
nickel package covering slot receivers. 
</P>
<P>
	24, SAN FRANCISCO -- The 49ers moved up three spots, dealing with  
Miami to get a shot at REGGIE McGREW, DT, FLORIDA. Clearly worried 
about Bryant Young's return from a severe leg injury, the Niners 
believe McGrew will plug gaps against the run. 
</P>
<P>
	25, GREEN BAY -- The Packers have taken some hits in the  
secondary, and to compete with the Vikings in the NFC Central, they 
must upgrade safety and cornerback. ANTWAN EDWARDS, S, CLEMSON, 
will allow Darren Sharper to move to cornerback. Edwards moves 
well, but needs work on tackling. 
</P>
<P>
	26, JACKSONVILLE -- Another good need pick. The Jaguars have few  
weaknesses, but their pass coverage is mediocre. They also wanted a 
good man-to-man guy and FERNANDO BRYANT, CB, ALABAMA, can handle 
that. But he also needs outside motivation. 
</P>
<P>
	27, DETROIT -- On a pick from Miami, the Lions filled another  
need -- did they ever -- with 380-pound AARON GIBSON, T-G, Wisconsin. 
Barry Sanders and Charlie Batch certainly don't mind having a 
road-grader like that. 
</P>
<P>
	28, NEW ENGLAND -- The Parcells pick. This is the last choice the  
Jets owed the Patriots, and it was used to take a big name whose 
game sagged in 1998: ANDY KATZENMOYER, LB, OHIO STATE. With Todd 
Collins gone, he might have to move outside. He won't displace Ted 
Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	29, MINNESOTA -- After their success with Randy Moss, the Vikings  
are unafraid of problem players. So they went for DIMITRIUS 
UNDERWOOD, DE, MICHIGAN STATE. He missed the season with an ankle 
injury and needs to mature. 
</P>
<P>
	30, ATLANTA -- The Falcons did well by getting PATRICK KERNEY,  
DE, VIRGINIA. A former lacrosse player, he brings intelligence and 
dedication and should enhance an already solid pass rush. But 
should they have gone after a wide receiver, an even bigger need? 
</P>
<P>
	31, DENVER -- From national champion to Super Bowl champion. Not  
bad for AL WILSON, LB, TENNESSEE. Eventually, Bill Romanowski must 
be replaced and Wilson, if he can stay healthy, should be the guy. 
</P>
<P>
	34, CAROLINA -- The lightest offensive lineman at the NFL Combine  
at 291 pounds, CHRIS TERRY, T, GEORGIA, isn't as good as college 
teammate Stinchcomb. He's a bit inexperienced, but Panthers need 
him to start. 
</P>
<P>
	39, MIAMI -- On a pick obtained from the Lions, Jimmy Johnson got  
a second-tier running back in JAMES JOHNSON, RB, MISSISSIPPI STATE. 
He isn't a breakaway threat, but is powerful and can catch. 
</P>
<P>
	57, NEW YORK JETS -- With a hole at guard, the Jets were anxious  
about RANDY THOMAS, G, MISSISSIPPI STATE, lasting this far. He did, 
and he could find himself starting in September. 
</P>
<P>
	60, SAN DIEGO -- Punishment for the Ryan Leaf trade meant no  
picks until the end of the second round. The choice, JERMAINE 
FAZANDE, FB, Oklahoma, was one of those reaches Bobby Beathard is 
known for. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
