<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  US Destroyer Bears Churchill's Name </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BATH, Maine (AP) -- A U.S. Navy destroyer was launched Saturday  
bearing the name of former British prime minister Sir Winston 
Churchill -- an honor rarely afforded foreigners. 
</P>
<P>
	Lady Soames, the former British leader's only living child,  
joined U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen, British Defense 
Minister George Robertson and other Churchill relatives to watch 
the 505-foot warship Winston S. Churchill slide down a greased ramp 
at the Bath Iron Works into the Kennebec River. 
</P>
<P>
	``The naming of this ship is very special and stands out in a  
class of its own,'' said Soames, 76, the youngest of his five 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen told a crowd of about 6,500 that Churchill ``gave the  
world hope in the darkest hours and helped shape the world that we 
know today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two peace activists, a man and a woman, were arrested after  
attempting to shout down Cohen and Maine Gov. Angus King during 
each of their remarks. They were released charged with disorderly 
conduct and released. About 55 people outside demonstrated for 
peace. 
</P>
<P>
	Churchill served as Britain's fiery prime minister from 1940 to  
1945 and from 1951 to 1955. He vowed during the early days of World 
War II that his country would never fall to Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	``We shall defend our island whatever the cost may be,'' he told  
the House of Commons while the specter of German invasion loomed. 
``We shall fight on beaches, on landing grounds, fields, in streets 
and on the hills. We shall never surrender.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The $950 million vessel will weigh more than 8,000 tons when  
fully loaded and delivered to the Navy. Advanced radar enables the 
Arleigh Burke-class destroyer to simultaneously wage battle with 
planes, ships and submarines. 
</P>
<P>
	The warship's arsenal will include Tomahawk cruise missiles,  
Harpoon missiles and torpedoes. It is built to withstand chemical 
attacks and is capable of speeds up to 30 knots. 
</P>
<P>
	Sixteen other U.S. ships have been named after foreign heroes,  
five for Britons. None are in active service. 
</P>
<P>
	Churchill, however, was declared an honorary U.S. citizen in  
1963, two years before his death. His mother was American. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain named an attack submarine in honor of Churchill 20 years  
ago. The vessel was removed from service in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 12:13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Timberwolves Sign Guard Robinson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Guard James ``Hollywood'' Robinson has signed  
a contract to play with the Minnesota Timberwolves for the rest of 
the season, the team announced Saturday. Terms were not immediately 
disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wolves had signed Robinson to back-to-back 10-day contracts  
after the Los Angeles Clippers released him March 18. 
</P>
<P>
	He scored a season-high 15 points in Friday night's 89-75  
victory over Vancouver and had a season-high seven assists against 
Houston in Monday's 95-90 loss. 
</P>
<P>
	This is Robinson's second stint with the Timberwolves. He spent  
the 1996-97 season with Minnesota after the Wolves acquired him 
from Portland in the Isaiah Rider trade in July 1996. He left 
Minnesota to sign a free-agent contract with the Clippers in August 
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 11:09:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> D.C. Spruces Up for NATO Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An army of civil servants, corporate  
volunteers, federal planners and law enforcement officers is 
mobilizing to help the nation's capital prepare as host of its 
largest gathering of world leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the North Atlantic Treaty Organization returns for  
three days to the city where President Truman and the leaders of a 
handful of other nations created NATO in 1949. The now-19 NATO 
nations will be joined by officials from 25 eastern and central 
European partner countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an opportunity to showcase Washington, D.C. as a  
beautiful city,'' said Mayor Anthony Williams. ``We're also the 
co-host with the president and the first lady.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The event, with some 40 heads of government, 2,500 to 3,000  
media and 1,700 dignitaries, is a huge logistical challenge, said 
Dana Shelley, spokeswoman for the NATO 50th Summit Host Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor has ordered a massive cleanup of areas of the city  
that don't normally appear on postcards. Vacant lots are being 
fenced, graffiti wiped out, trees trimmed and streets swept. 
</P>
<P>
	Plans call for foreign delegations to arrive at Ronald Reagan  
National and Dulles airports in Virginia and the 
Baltimore-Washington International Airport and Andrews Air Force 
Base in Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	``That means cleaning our gateways - Georgia Avenue, New York  
Avenue - the ways that people come into our city, and then cleaning 
the neighborhoods around them,'' said Kay McGrath, a special 
assistant to the mayor. ``What one weekend does is, it helps you 
reposition the District of Columbia into its rightful position as 
the capital of the free world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	City officials see it as a prime opportunity to market  
Washington's prestige addresses -- the Capitol Hill area, portions 
of New York and Pennsylvania avenues -- in a continuing effort to 
spur economic revitalization. 
</P>
<P>
	Seventeen law enforcement agencies, including the Secret  
Service, FBI, Metropolitan Police Department and National Park 
Service Police, will provide security. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers will be prepared for unrest. ``It would be  
un-American not to have at least some demonstrators,'' said Richard 
Socarides, chief operating officer for summit organizers, 
explaining that a specific area will be designated for protesters 
granted permits. 
</P>
<P>
	Except for areas where summit events are planned, streets will  
be open and vendors will be allowed to remain, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will have rolling street closures,'' as motorcades for the  
40 heads of state move through, said Cmdr. Michael Radzilowski, 
head of the city police department's Special Operations Division. 
</P>
<P>
	``Washington, D.C. is a tough town for traffic anyway, and  
moving these folks around is a tough task for us,'' said Maj. 
General Joseph Garrett, the vice director of the NATO summit 
planning staff. 
</P>
<P>
	Soldiers from Fort Eustis, Va., are being brought in to drive  
shuttle buses and cars for dignitaries. In addition, most 
government offices near summit sites will be closed Friday to 
reduce traffic. About half the 180,000 area federal employees and 
7,500 district government workers will receive the day off with 
pay. 
</P>
<P>
	The region's subway will travel through, but not stop, at the  
Federal Triangle subway stop near the main summit site, the Ronald 
Reagan International Trade Center downtown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
