<DOCNO> APW19990417.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 08:13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kiwi May Fly Again Under FAA Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Kiwi International Air Lines, awash in debt  
and without planes or permission to fly, reached a deal with 
federal regulators that could get it off the ground again, the 
airline said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement with the Federal Aviation Administration is the  
latest time that the 7-year-old airline bounced back when its 
demise seemed assured. 
</P>
<P>
	Newark-based Kiwi was to appeal the FAA's revocation of its  
flight certification on Tuesday before the National Transportation 
Safety Board. That hearing is now off. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA, without warning, pulled Kiwi's license on March 24,  
saying the carrier was unable to fly its six-city schedule safely. 
Thousands of travelers, some already at airports, were left without 
flights or reservations. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiwi laid off nearly all of its 500 workers and surrendered its  
four leased jets, but won permission from a bankruptcy judge to 
keep a skeleton staff in place to press its appeal of the 
revocation. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, the FAA changed the revocation to a  
suspension and will assess no fines or penalties, Kiwi spokesman 
Rob Kulat said. The suspension could last up to four months while 
the FAA completes a review, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very pleased to have reached an understanding with the  
FAA and to begin the process of the airline's reorganization,'' 
Charles Stanziale, Kiwi's trustee, said in a statement issued 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	FAA spokeswoman Arlene Salac said Kiwi would be allowed to  
reapply for certification. 
</P>
<P>
	``They would have to prove to us they can operate in a safe and  
efficient manner,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Charles C. Edwards, a Baltimore surgeon who had been the  
airline's chairman until Stanziale was appointed to oversee its 
assets on April 1, called the settlement a ``wonderful 
vindication.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``No matter how strained it ever became financially, never was  
one shortcut made in maintenance or safety,'' Edwards said. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal gives Kiwi another chance to attract someone to rescue  
it from bankruptcy, and provide cash so it can lease some jets and 
rehire workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Pan Am Airways, a former commercial airliner that flies charters  
out of Portsmouth, N.H., offered to buy Kiwi last month for $3 
million. But that plan collapsed when Kiwi could not immediately 
restore its flight certificate. 
</P>
<P>
	Before being grounded, Kiwi served Newark; Miami, Orlando and  
Palm Beach, Fla.; and San Juan and Aguadilla, Puerto Rico. 
</P>
<P>
	At its peak in the mid-90s, Kiwi had 1,200 workers, and they  
owned a controlling share of the airline, which boasted 15 leased 
jets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 16:22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  US Destroyer Bears Churchill's Name </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BATH, Maine (AP) -- A U.S. Navy destroyer was launched Saturday  
bearing the name of former British prime minister Sir Winston 
Churchill -- an honor rarely afforded foreigners. 
</P>
<P>
	Lady Soames, the former British leader's only living child,  
joined U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen, British Defense 
Minister George Robertson and other Churchill relatives to watch 
the 505-foot warship Winston S. Churchill slide down a greased ramp 
at the Bath Iron Works into the Kennebec River. 
</P>
<P>
	``The naming of this ship is very special and stands out in a  
class of its own,'' said Soames, 76, the youngest of his five 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen told a crowd of about 6,500 that Churchill ``gave the  
world hope in the darkest hours and helped shape the world that we 
know today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two peace activists, a man and a woman, were arrested after  
attempting to shout down Cohen and Maine Gov. Angus King during 
each of their remarks. They were released charged with disorderly 
conduct and released. About 55 people outside demonstrated for 
peace. 
</P>
<P>
	Churchill served as Britain's fiery prime minister from 1940 to  
1945 and from 1951 to 1955. He vowed during the early days of World 
War II that his country would never fall to Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	``We shall defend our island whatever the cost may be,'' he told  
the House of Commons while the specter of German invasion loomed. 
``We shall fight on beaches, on landing grounds, fields, in streets 
and on the hills. We shall never surrender.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The $950 million vessel will weigh more than 8,000 tons when  
fully loaded and delivered to the Navy. Advanced radar enables the 
Arleigh Burke-class destroyer to simultaneously wage battle with 
planes, ships and submarines. 
</P>
<P>
	The warship's arsenal will include Tomahawk cruise missiles,  
Harpoon missiles and torpedoes. It is built to withstand chemical 
attacks and is capable of speeds up to 30 knots. 
</P>
<P>
	Sixteen other U.S. ships have been named after foreign heroes,  
five for Britons. None are in active service. 
</P>
<P>
	Churchill, however, was declared an honorary U.S. citizen in  
1963, two years before his death. His mother was American. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain named an attack submarine in honor of Churchill 20 years  
ago. The vessel was removed from service in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
