<DOCNO> APW19990417.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 18:12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Braves' Rocker Blow First Save Opp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- John Rocker doesn't have a grunge-rock haircut or  
an intimidating goatee like some major league closers, but he's 
adopting the attitude real quick. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're either the damn hero or the goat,'' Rocker said  
Saturday after giving up three ninth-inning runs in the Atlanta 
Braves' 5-4 loss to the Colorado Rockies. ``I'm not going to change 
my pitching philosophy. I'm fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rocker, 24, inherited Atlanta's closing job when Kerry  
Ligtenberg went down with an elbow injury and Mark Wohlers was 
traded after an ongoing battle with his control. 
</P>
<P>
	With a 100 mph fastball, the left-handed Rocker has the  
potential to be dominating. He struck out six of the first seven 
hitters he faced this year but struggled Saturday, walking two and 
giving up a two-run single to Angel Echevarria to tie it at 4. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like facing guys who throw like that because you have to  
make up your mind really, really quick,'' said Echevarria, who was 
1-for-9 before his groundball single between third and shortstop. 
</P>
<P>
	Echevarria pounced on a slider, as did Darryl Hamilton, who  
handed Rocker his first loss of the year when he slapped a line 
drive to left-center. The turn of events left Rocker with a scowl 
to match the image of pro wrestler ``Stone Cold'' Steve Austin 
staring out from his T-shirt. 
</P>
<P>
	``He just fouled a 100 mph fastball straight back and the next  
pitch I throw him a good slider 15 mph slower and he's right on 
that, too,'' Rocker said of Hamilton. ``How are you right on both 
of those pitches? I don't know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rocker's breakdown spoiled a solid performance by Atlanta  
starter Tom Glavine (0-2), who is still trying to avoid his first 
0-3 start since 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no question it would have been nice to get that first  
win under my belt, but it didn't happen,'' Glavine said. ``I feel 
good about what I did today, and it's something to build on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For his part, Rocker learned a lesson familiar to even the best  
of closers: You can't save them all. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll think about that a little bit, but (Glavine) will have  
other chances,'' Rocker said. ``I'll have other chances to save 
games.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
