<DOCNO> APW19990417.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 00:42:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Halts Schott's Sale of Reds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Marge Schott's attempt to sell control of the  
Cincinnati Reds to a cousin has been blocked by a judge. 
</P>
<P>
	The team's limited partners got a temporary restraining order  
Friday preventing Schott from doing anything until a Hamilton 
County Common Pleas judge hears the case. 
</P>
<P>
	The order came one day after the limited partners sued, claiming  
Schott had entered into a ``contrived'' agreement with cousin Steve 
Schott to prevent them from buying her out. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Robert Ruehlman granted the partners' request for a  
temporary restraining order during a closed hearing in his 
chambers. A full hearing was scheduled for April 29. 
</P>
<P>
	James Burke, a lawyer for the partners, was pleased by the  
ruling but declined further comment. Schott did not return messages 
seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Documents filed with the court show that Schott is trying to  
retain a high profile with the club even after she sells her 
controlling shares. 
</P>
<P>
	She agreed to sell last November rather than face another  
suspension from major league baseball. Schott, who took over the 
team in the mid-1980s, can be forced out by the limited partners 
when the current ownership agreement expires at the end of 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	She signed a preliminary purchase agreement on Feb. 11 with  
Larry Dolan, the brother of Cablevision Systems Corp.'s chairman, 
to sell all but one of her 6 1/2 shares for $65 million. She scrawled 
a dog's paw and ``02'' next to her signature, an indication that 
her St. Bernard also approved. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal included guarantees that she would maintain her office  
at Cinergy Field and have an office in the club's new ballpark, 
scheduled to open in 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	It also said she would have a private luxury suite in the new  
stadium and access to 16 lower-level seats. She also would have 
input on team matters. 
</P>
<P>
	Major league baseball has final say over any deal and most  
likely would reject any provision that keeps Schott in a high 
profile. She has repeatedly been disciplined by the other owners 
for inflammatory remarks. 
</P>
<P>
	The limited partners have the right to match any offer for  
Schott's shares within 30 days and sent Schott a letter saying they 
would match Dolan's offer on April 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The next day, Schott sent the partners a letter rejecting their  
matching offer, claiming Dolan's offer ``does not exist.'' She also 
said she would enter into another deal. 
</P>
<P>
	A letter from Dolan dated April 1 said Schott was ``mistaken''  
and emphasized that he still intended to buy her shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Monday, Schott informed the partners of a deal to sell her  
shares for $67 million to a group that includes Steve Schott. He 
would receive an estimated $2.68 million payment for his role in 
arranging the sale. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal with her cousin gives Schott even more favorable  
treatment after she sells. In addition to an office and luxury 
suite at the ballpark, she would get 21 tickets and an opportunity 
to participate in the annual opening day parade. 
</P>
<P>
	Whoever purchases her shares also would contribute $250,000  
toward naming rights to a team museum in the new stadium. It would 
be called the ``Schott Hall of Fame/Museum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The limited partners want Ruehlman to rule that Steve Schott's  
offer is invalid and that the partners have properly matched 
Dolan's deal, clearing the way for them to buy controlling 
interest. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 15:12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Backs Elder Protection Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The greatest threat older Americans now face  
is not a gun-wielding thug but ``a telemarketer armed with a 
deceptive rap,'' President Clinton said Saturday. He proposed 
legislation to shut down telephone scams aimed at the elderly. 
</P>
<P>
	The president said also that while the sharply falling crime  
rate is a godsend to older people who once fearfully locked 
themselves into their homes, new protection is needed for nursing 
home residents who ``cannot lock the door against abuse and neglect 
by the people paid to care for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton used his weekly radio address to promote the crime bill  
he will send to Congress next month. He said it will impose ``tough 
measures to target people who prey on elderly Americans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal also aims at those who defraud health care plans or  
steal from pensions and retirement funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., sponsor of existing legislation to  
guard the elderly from abuse and fraud, endorsed the president's 
efforts. ``We must strengthen the hands of law enforcement to 
combat those predators who plunder the savings that older Americans 
have worked a lifetime to earn,'' Leahy said. 
</P>
<P>
	And Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, chairman of the Senate  
Special Committee on Aging, said he also agrees with the 
president's priorities. ``As the number of older Americans grows, 
so does the number of scams targeting them,'' Grassley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Telemarketing fraud cheats Americans of an estimated $40 billion  
a year, and more than half the victims are over 50, Clinton said. 
``That's like a fraud tax aimed directly at senior citizens,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton bill would give the Justice Department authority to  
cancel telephone service when evidence is found of an illegal 
telemarketing operation. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you prey on older Americans, we will cut off your phone  
lines and shut you down,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The president said his administration has already issued rules  
to govern nursing home operations and has stepped up investigations 
of possible abuse or neglect. 
</P>
<P>
	``But when one out of four nursing homes in America does not  
provide quality care ... and when people living in substandard 
nursing homes have as much fear from abuse and neglect as they do 
from the diseases of old age, we must do more,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill gives the Justice Department authority to investigate,  
prosecute and punish operators of nursing homes found to have 
repeatedly abused or neglected residents. Proposed penalties 
include 10-year jail terms for individuals and fines for nursing 
home chains of up to $2 million for each home where residents are 
neglected or abused. 
</P>
<P>
	The president's proposal permits the department seek court  
orders to stop nursing homes from mistreating patients. The plan 
also protects whistle-blowers who tell officials about wrongdoing 
in nursing homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
