<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> El-Amin Still a Hit With the Fans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A parade honoring national champion  
Connecticut provided a smooth ending Saturday to what had been a 
very rough week for popular point guard Khalid El-Amin. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5-foot-10 sophomore was arrested on marijuana charges  
Tuesday, 15 days after leading his team to the national title over 
Duke. By Thursday, he had delivered a public apology to his team 
and fans. On Friday, he helped pick up trash as part of his 
community service that will wipe his record clean in 30 days. 
</P>
<P>
	And on Saturday, as he rode atop a flatbed on the 1 1/2-mile route,  
he was clearly the fan favorite. His fans delivered the message 
loud and clear that they were ready to forgive and forget. 
</P>
<P>
	``He deserves to be here,'' Rudy Vogel said. ``He means a lot to  
this team. He's the one that pumps them all up. He's the one who 
gets them going. He just made a mistake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Donna Campbell couldn't wipe the giant smile off her face after  
El-Amin called out to her ``I love you.'' He waved and threw kisses 
back at her as she made her affection known. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am in love with El-Amin,'' she said. ``I hate what happened  
the other day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elena Lojardi arrived four hours before the start of the parade  
to get a prime spot on the route. 
</P>
<P>
	She unfurled a banner that read: ``Khalid El-Amin We Support  
You.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a good guy. He's got a good heart and he always means  
well,'' she said. ``He's a big reason why this day is happening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He certainly loomed large nearly three weeks ago. El-Amin coolly  
sank two free throws with five seconds remaining in the title game. 
They were the final points in the Huskies' 77-74 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	El-Amin, 19, said he was grateful for the outpouring.  
</P>
<P>
	``I feel comfortable that the fans still support me, and they  
did it in such a way that I really felt it and really am 
appreciative of that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The team members donned T-shirts that adorned with the slogan  
``Mission Accomplished.'' They blew kisses back to the crowd, and 
signed everything from basketballs to pennants that were tossed 
their way. 
</P>
<P>
	Capitol police said more than 250,000 people turned out for the  
parade. There were some scary moments. A young girl was injured 
when she darted into the street and was hit by a police motorcycle. 
</P>
<P>
	As hundreds of children and adults crowded around the team float  
tossing shirts, balls and caps to the players to sign, a few 
youngsters became separated from their parents in the crush. Police 
said by parade's end, all had been reunited. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Jim Calhoun and his wife, Pat, sat atop a red convertible  
just ahead of the team. Calhoun, who arrived at UConn 13 years ago, 
said the emotions of the day were ``absolutely astounding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The championship marked UConn's first trip to the Final Four in  
21 tries. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not only did the championship capture the state,'' Calhoun  
said. ``I can tell you right now, it's certainly captured us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the parade, Calhoun and senior captains Rashamel Jones and  
Ricky Moore addressed nearly 70,000 people on the lawn of the state 
Capitol in a rally that included remarks from Gov. John G. Rowland, 
university officials and state lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	``On behalf of the team, we simply want to say `We love you',''  
said Calhoun. 
</P>
<P>
	``You gave us motivation all year long,'' said Moore, whose  
tough defense bottled up the Duke attack. 
</P>
<P>
	El-Amin did admit there may have been a point during the day  
when he disappointed some fans. Tossing the right autographed 
T-shirt or cap back to the right kid, he said, was more difficult 
that feeding a teammate with an alley-oop pass. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a couple shirts I got from one side and I went to the  
other side and threw it over there. So I know there's a lot of fans 
out there that are upset at me,'' he said. ``But I hope they'll 
understand.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
