<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fans Bid Farewell to BoxCar Willie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) -- It was BoxCar Willie's last public  
appearance, and it drew a full house as about 900 people filled the 
Branson entertainer's theater to say goodbye to America's singing 
hobo. 
</P>
<P>
	BoxCar Willie, whose given name was Lecil Martin, died last week  
of leukemia at age 67. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the mourners who crowded in to the BoxCar Willie Theater  
on Branson's strip Saturday afternoon were many of the mountain 
music town's biggest stars, including Mel Tillis, Andy Williams, 
Jim Stafford and Yakov Smirnoff, and nearly each one had a warm 
memory to share about the years they had known the entertainer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We served in the Air Force together, in Lincoln, Neb., 45  
years ago,'' Tillis recalled after the 45-minute service. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was a baker and he was a flight engineer. He used to come by  
the place where I did my baking, and we'd sit on the flour sacks 
and pick our guitars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also among the mourners were family, friends and fans of the  
entertainer, though BoxCar Willie fans for the most part considered 
themselves his friends as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Many had come to his theater several times over the years since  
he had arrived in Branson in 1986 and had gotten to know him 
visiting backstage after performances. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them were Mary Lee Mousel and her husband Ronald, who came  
from Hollister. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are really going to miss him,'' she said. ``We've been  
praying for him to make it back. We just pray that he is with the 
Lord now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The funeral, meanwhile, was as much a celebration of the  
entertainer's life as a chance to mourn his passing. 
</P>
<P>
	The performer was seen in several video clips from his show over  
the years singing such songs as ``The Wabash Cannonball'' and 
``I've Seen It All From a Boxcar Door.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As several people in the audience wept, including some veterans  
who had served with BoxCar Willie during the 22 years he spent in 
the Air Force, the Rev. Cliff Braschler told them not to fear 
death. 
</P>
<P>
	He said BoxCar Willie loved life and lived to enjoy every moment  
of it and, because of that, he didn't fear death either. 
</P>
<P>
	On that subject, BoxCar Willie himself seemed to have the last  
word when mourners heard him sing: 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll ride that last train to heaven, on rails of solid gold,  
</P>
<P>
	``In a boxcar filled with satin, where the nights are never  
cold. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where the hobo's always welcome, even in his raggedy clothes.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'll ride that last train to heaven, when the final whistle  
blows.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
