<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 00:31:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers' Rambis Wanted Rodman Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- To Los Angeles Lakers coach Kurt Rambis, it  
was a pretty easy call -- he believes his team will be better off 
without Dennis Rodman. 
</P>
<P>
	An indication could come as soon as tonight in Utah when the  
Lakers begin the post-Rodman era. 
</P>
<P>
	Rambis hit the wall after yet another incident involving Rodman  
at Thursday's practice, and that led to the release of the 
seven-time NBA rebounding champion later in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Lakers management acted swiftly and decisively in support of the  
man named coach on Feb. 26, coincidentally the same day Rodman 
played his first game with the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a time where we need an ultimate focus and  
concentration,'' Rambis said after Friday's practice and just 
before the Lakers left for Salt Lake City, where they'll face the 
powerful Jazz in a nationally televised game. ``I just think this 
is better for the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rodman, who turns 38 next month, has had a terrific career and  
has been a part of five championship teams, including the last 
three with the Chicago Bulls. 
</P>
<P>
	However, his unreliability has been an issue for years, although  
the Michael Jordan-led Bulls generally kept him in line. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers don't have a Michael Jordan. And now, they don't have  
Rodman. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it was justified,'' Lakers standout Kobe Bryant said  
when asked his opinion of the move to place Rodman on waivers. 
``When a guy shows up continuously late ... Yeah, it was definitely 
justified.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Bryant also said, ``I'm a little disappointed. I wanted  
Dennis to hang around. Winning cures everything. He helped us out, 
to be honest with you. When he was here, he did provide us with a 
lot of energy. I would love to have Dennis right now. If we had won 
the last two games, he would still be here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But they didn't win the last two, losing 113-109 to Seattle at  
the Forum on Sunday and 113-86 at Portland on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rambis claimed he had a sore left elbow and didn't play at all  
in the second half at Portland. It was the fourth time in his 23 
games with the team he had opted not to return to a game. 
</P>
<P>
	Then came Thursday. According to Rambis, Rodman arrived late for  
the team's practice at Los Angeles Southwest College and was slow 
getting ready because he couldn't find his socks and shoes. 
</P>
<P>
	Rambis sent him home, and later had a pointed conversation with  
club executives Jerry West and Mitch Kupchak. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodman had not been given an ultimatum before Thursday, Rambis  
said, adding he was disappointed the move had to be made because of 
what Rodman had shown what he was capable of doing. 
</P>
<P>
	``The in-and-out just got to be too much,'' Rambis said. ``I  
felt we needed everyone to be on the same page. I gave my 
recommendation to management, a minimum of a suspension. It was my 
belief we should waive him at this time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And that's what happened.  
</P>
<P>
	Speaking by telephone from Phoenix, Kupchak said the move  
probably wouldn't have been made at this time had Rambis not spoken 
up. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kurt and our staff keep us apprised daily,'' Kupchak said.  
``Quite frankly, the recommendation that Kurt made, we readily 
agreed to. We can't make that decision because we're not the ones 
at practices, at the games. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a culmination of acts that led to the waiver.  
(Thursday's) act alone would have never led to this kind of action. 
It's another in a series of actions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Steiner, a spokesman for Lakers owner Jerry Buss, said Buss'  
reaction to the move was, ``They did what they had to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kupchak said to the best of his knowledge as of late Friday  
nobody with the team had spoken with Rodman after he was sent home 
from Thursday's practice, although Steiner said he believed Buss 
would make an attempt to speak with the now ex-Laker as a friend. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Buss and Lakers center Shaquille O'Neal who were most in  
favor of signing Rodman. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Neal declined to speak with reporters after Friday's practice.  
</P>
<P>
	Kupchak said he tried to call Rodman late Thursday and spoke to  
his representative and bodyguard, but Rodman didn't return phone 
messages. 
</P>
<P>
	Kupchak said Steve Chasman, Rodman's agent, acted surprised  
about the move. 
</P>
<P>
	``I find it difficult to believe he was surprised,'' Kupchak  
said. ``We try to do things the right way. Everything we do is well 
thought out. This is a decision we had to make. We're the ones who 
have to make these decisions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kupchak had words of praise for Rambis, saying, ``Jerry (West)  
and I feel Kurt has done a wonderful job. Regarding Dennis, he 
handled it the same way Jerry and I would have handled it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Matt Labov, Rodman's publicist, refused comment Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers (25-15) have 10 games remaining before the playoffs,  
starting with their game against the Jazz (30-8), winners of nine 
straight games. Utah has the NBA's best record. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodman's place on the roster was taken by forward Travis Knight,  
who was activated from the injured list. 
</P>
<P>
	Rambis said J.R. Reid would replace Rodman in the starting  
lineup against the Jazz. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 11:16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> $105M Man Savaged by Padres Fans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- It was all about the money when Kevin Brown  
returned to the mound at Qualcomm Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Padres' fans, who lovingly cheered their team even after it was  
swept in the World Series, delighted in savaging Brown, who in turn 
was cashed in by his former teammates on his first visit to San 
Diego since October. 
</P>
<P>
	The boos began 25 minutes before Friday night's game, when Brown  
began running warmups in the outfield. They reached a crescendo 
when his name was called in the Los Angeles Dodgers' starting 
lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	As Brown threw his warmup pitches in the bottom of the first  
inning, the Beatles' ``Can't Buy Me Love'' blared from the sound 
system. Pink Floyd's ``Money'' led off the bottom of the fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	The Beatles tune was played at the suggestion of owner John  
Moores, who offered $60 million over six years in an attempt to 
keep Brown, the hired gun whose intensity rubbed off on the Padres 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, of course, snubbed that offer and became baseball's first  
$100 million man, getting $105 million over seven years from the 
Dodgers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope we clean his clock,'' Moores said in the Padres dugout  
before the game. ``That's what we're supposed to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moores got his wish. Brown couldn't buy a win, losing his first  
decision of the year, 3-0, as the Padres' new ace, Andy Ashby, was 
brilliant in throwing a five-hitter. 
</P>
<P>
	Moores even suggested that the Padres leave Brown's NL  
championship ring on home plate. He'll get it sometime this 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, Brown was largely responsible for getting the Padres to the  
World Series, which in turn got them a new downtown ballpark 
approved by the voters less than two weeks after being swept by the 
New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	But that seemed like ancient history to the crowd of 48,943,  
which provided a playoff-like atmosphere on a perfect spring night. 
</P>
<P>
	When Dodgers manager Davey Johnson walked out to remove Brown in  
the seventh after Wally Joyner's RBI double put the Padres up 3-0, 
the fans stood and roared. The final boos of the night came as 
Brown walked slowly toward the dugout. One man leaned over the 
railing, flashing cash at the right-hander. 
</P>
<P>
	As he exited, Brown, who's from Macon, was serenaded by Gladys  
Knight and the Pips' ``Midnight Train To Georgia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moments earlier, a life-size pinata resembling Brown, hanging by  
the neck from a stick, was smashed apart by the Padres' Friar 
mascot. Fake dollar bills tumbled out. 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Gwynn, who had his second three-hit game of the season to  
pull within 55 of 3,000, said it wasn't necessarily the worst he's 
seen Padres fans. They love to bash Barry Bonds and pillory Mike 
Piazza. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was spirited, I'll say that.'' Gwynn said of the fans. I  
didn't think it would be like it was, but they paid their money. 
They're entitled to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Padres players, including Gwynn, spoke of respect for Brown.  
</P>
<P>
	Manager Bruce Bochy did too, but also seemed to side with the  
fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't know what kind of reaction they'd have,'' Bochy said.  
``Hey, it's our park. It's good for the game, I mean, it definitely 
brought a lot more attention to the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's real strange seeing him in a different uniform. That's  
part of the game. It's baseball now in the 90s. Hey, we all make 
decisions. It's behind us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby called it a difficult situation for Brown.  
</P>
<P>
	``I have a lot of respect for Brownie,'' he said. ``If anyone  
can handle it, he sure can, I guarantee that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, the loser in Game 4 of the World Series, claimed it was  
no worse than playing in Atlanta, or in Houston during last year's 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they want to boo, that's their choice,'' he said. ``The  
Dodgers aren't real popular down here. I don't think they were last 
year, either.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown took the musical razzing in stride.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's not my song, so I didn't pay attention to it,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
