<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Serbs Pushing To Clear Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- As Serb forces appeared to be making  
a final push to clear Kosovo of its ethnic Albanian population amid 
NATO airstrikes against Yugoslavia, thousands of refugees were on 
the move today. At least 5,000 refugees crossed into Macedonia 
yesterday, and 8,000 arrived in Albania by late afternoon. More 
were expected today. Ron Redmont, a spokesman for the U.N. High 
Commissioner for Refugees, said an enormous new wave -- more than 
100,000 refugees -- was believed bound for Macedonia alone. 

</P>
<P>
	US Holds Yugoslav Soldier  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States is holding a Yugoslav Army  
officer. Pentagon officials yesterday said Kosovo Liberation Army 
soldiers captured the officer, who was found to be in good 
condition following a medical examination. The International Red 
Cross is expected to visit the officer, and U.S. authorities are 
arranging ``religious counseling'' for him. He is being held as a 
prisoner of war in the Albanian capital of Tirana. 

</P>
<P>
	Arafat, Gadhafi To Talk in Libya  
</P>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat was in  
Libya today for talks with Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi, Egypt's 
Middle East News Agency reported. Arafat has been on a tour of 
world capitals to gather support for the declaration of a 
Palestinian state on May 4. He has visited Japan, India, Pakistan, 
Indonesia, Yemen, Russia, Turkey and China 

</P>
<P>
	Bhutto Supporters Call Strike  
</P>
<P>
	KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) -- A strike call to protest the conviction  
of embattled former Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto spurred walkouts 
in her ancestral home today but was largely ignored in Karachi, 
Pakistan's largest city. Ms. Bhutto and her jailed husband, Asif 
Ali Zardari, were convicted Thursday of corruption and abuse of 
power, and sentenced to five years in jail, fined $8.6 million and 
disqualified from politics. The court also ordered their property 
confiscated. 

</P>
<P>
	Greenspan Frets About Protectionism  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan  
expressed concern yesterday that Americans are losing faith in the 
benefits of free trade. ``The evidence is overwhelmingly persuasive 
that the massive increase in world competition -- a consequence of 
broadening trade flows -- has fostered markedly higher standards of 
living for almost all countries who have participated,'' Greenspan 
said in a speech to foreign ambassadors. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-'Waltons' Star Corby Dies  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Ellen Corby, who played the tart-tongued  
country grandmother on television's ``The Waltons'' and was an 
Oscar nominee for the 1948 film ``I Remember Mama,'' has died. She 
was 87. Corby died Wednesday at the Motion Picture &AMP; Television 
Hospital after an extended illness, a hospital spokeswoman said 
yesterday. She appeared in more than 100 movies, including 
``Shane'' (1953), ``Sabrina'' (1954) and ``Vertigo'' (1958). Her 
performance as the lovelorn aunt in ``I Remember Mama,'' starring 
Irene Dunne, earned her the Academy Award bid. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Organ Donation Up 5.6 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of organ donors increased 5.6  
percent last year, enabling about 600 more transplants in 1998 over 
1997 and marking the first substantial increase in three years, 
according to the Department of Health and Human Services. The 
increase was most dramatic among donors age 60 and older, who have 
traditionally been passed over by organ banks and hospitals because 
their hearts, kidneys and livers tend to be less healthy than 
organs from younger patients. 

</P>
<P>
	No Charges in Internet Death Case  
</P>
<P>
	FARMINGTON HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- A man whose Internet romance with  
a French woman ended in her apparent suicide won't face charges in 
her death, authorities said yesterday. Police have said Julie Yasa, 
28, traveled to the United States in February to meet the 
24-year-old man after a six-month e-mail relationship. After a 
one-time sexual encounter, the man drove Ms. Yasa to a motel, then 
turned her away when she showed up at his apartment, police said. 
Her body was found March 3 near the man's apartment. She died after 
taking an excessive dose of a sleep aid. 

</P>
<P>
	76ers Beat Pacers 93-83  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Allen Iverson broke open a tight,  
playoff-like game with a hardfought steal in the closing minutes 
and scored 26 points as the Philadelphia Sixers beat the Indiana 
Pacers 93-83 last night. It was Philadelphia's second straight 
victory over Indiana after losing 10 in a row. 

</P>
<P>
	Gretzky Ends a Magnificent Career  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Wayne Gretzky remained composed yesterday as he  
announced his retirement following several months of agonized 
self-searching. The hard part will come Sunday when he takes off 
his skates for the last time following the New York Rangers' game 
with the Pittsburgh Penguins at Madison Square Garden. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
