<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 04:13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 1973 Murder Conviction Overturned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- A man who spent 26 years behind bars was  
released from prison after a judge overturned his murder conviction 
due to suppressed evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	However, John Duval's legal troubles may not be over. After he  
was released Friday, prosecutors said they may retry him for the 
1973 killing of a businessman. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our position is that he was certainly properly convicted of  
these crimes and guilty of these crimes,'' said Assistant District 
Attorney Robert Mastrocola. ``That's still our position. But that 
doesn't necessarily mean we're ... going to re-try him. There's a 
lot of other things that go into this, more practical concerns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duval was greeted by an exultant knot of family, friends and  
supporters following his release. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad to be home, and that's all I've got to say,'' Duval  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	His mother, Betty Duval-Rutley, said she had already dropped by  
a supermarket to prepare him a special meal. 
</P>
<P>
	Duval's conviction was overturned April 5. A judge ruled that a  
one-page report of a police interview in which a teen-ager accuser 
initially claimed he never saw Duval and co-defendant Betty Tyson 
with the victim was never turned over to the defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson had her conviction dismissed last May for the same reason.  
The 50-year-old had spent half her life in prison and became New 
York's longest-serving female inmate. 
</P>
<P>
	Duval and Tyson, both former prostitutes, maintained they signed  
confessions only after being severely beaten by the police, who had 
no physical evidence linking them to the killing of Timothy 
Haworth. 
</P>
<P>
	A Philadelphia businessman and consultant to Eastman Kodak Co.,  
Haworth was apparently soliciting a prostitute on the night he was 
strangled on May 25, 1973. In separate trials, Duval and Tyson were 
sentenced to 25 years to life in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, he twice told the state Parole Board that he  
killed Haworth. He says now he believed he would remain behind bars 
unless he admitted guilt. ``I wanted to go home, so I lied,'' he 
said in an affidavit. 
</P>
<P>
	Mastrocola said prosecutors would make their decision on whether  
to seek a retrial in the next few weeks. A hearing was set for May 
14. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
