<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Four Honored For Distance Running </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Johnny Kelley, known as Boston's Marathon Man, and  
three other outstanding runners have been elected into the National 
Distance Running Hall of Fame at Utica, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Joining the 91-year-old Kelley in the Hall are 1972 women's  
Boston Marathon winner Nina Kuscik, 1964 Olympic 10,000-meter gold 
medalist Billy Mills and five-time Olympian Francie Larrieu Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelley has competed in 62 Boston Marathons, winning twice and  
placing second seven times. Generally an active participant in race 
activities, he is missing Monday's marathon while recovering from 
colon surgery and pneumonia. 
</P>
<P>
	Kuscik's victory 27 years ago was the first time women were  
officially recognized at Boston. She also won then New York City 
Marathon in 1972-73. 
</P>
<P>
	Mills' triumph was one of the biggest upsets in Olympic history  
as he became the first American to win a gold medal in the 10,000. 
Larrieu Smith, a member of the USA Track and Field Hall of Fame, 
finished fifth in the 1988 Olympic 10,000. She has set 36 U.S. 
records. 
</P>
<P>
	The new members will be inducted July 10 in a ceremony at  
Utica. 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	DE HAVEN CARRIES AMERICAN HOPES: Rod De Haven is not impressed  
by being the only elite American man in Monday's Boston Marathon. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's no big deal,'' said the 32-year-old from Madison, Wis.,  
who works as a computer programer for an insurance company, coaches 
himself, and is married with three children. ``Americans don't 
consider running Boston anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	``If an American is going to run a marathon, he wants to make  
some money. That's the mindset of most Americans, because they 
can't beat the Kenyans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In this decade, only three Americans have finished in the top 10  
at Boston -- Mark Plaatjes, a transplanted South African, was sixth 
and Keith Brantly ninth in 1993, and Bob Kempainen placed seventh 
in 1994. Meanwhile, Kenyans have won the past eight races. 
</P>
<P>
	De Haven doesn't figure to crack the top 10 Monday, not off his  
career-best of 2 hours, 13 minutes, last year at the Chicago 
Marathon. 
</P>
<P>
	``If an American is going to run 2:13, why not go to Pittsburgh  
for the national championships, where that might win?'' De Haven 
said. ``If someone runs even 2:14 or 2:15 at Pittsburgh, he can 
make $5,000 or $10,000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Why doesn't De Haven follow his own advice?  
</P>
<P>
	For two reasons.  
</P>
<P>
	``I hope to get caught up in a fast Boston race and slice my  
time by at least one minute to 2:12,'' he said. ``If I can run 
2:12, I will be in the top 10. Right now, running a fast time is 
more important than picking up a paycheck. 
</P>
<P>
	``Also, I picked Boston because of its tradition. At my age, I  
won't have too many other chances to run Boston.'' 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	DE REUCK HOPEFUL: South African Colleen de Reuck has come into  
the Boston Marathon three times with great expectations and left 
each time with tremendous disappointment. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-time road racer of the year finished ninth in her Boston  
debut in 1994, was third in 1997 and fifth last year. This year, de 
Reuck believes she can overcome her Boston jinx and end the 
two-year winning streak of Fatuma Roba of Ethiopia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I have the speed to beat her,'' de Reuck said, ``But  
you have to maintain. The top girls all have the caliber to win. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know what I have to do to win -- I can't go out too fast. I  
will have to run a good, even pace. Boston is very different from 
all other courses because of the uphills and downhills. Boston 
beats you up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	De Reuck keeps coming back, though, because of the ``special  
magic'' of the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of the top marathons in the world,'' she said. ``The  
course is a challenge, and I like challenges.'' 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	KAGWE CHASING WORLD RECORD: John Kagwe, winner of the past two  
New York City Marathons and one of the top contenders in Monday's 
Boston Marathon, has designs on breaking the world record of 2 
hours, 6 minutes, 5 seconds, by Brazil's Ronaldo daCosta. But he 
probably won't do it in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Kagwe has run Boston three times without much success. He  
finished 16th in his debut in 1994, did not finish in '96 and was 
fifth last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kenyans have run very fast, but they haven't had the blessing  
of the record,'' Kagwe said. ``I want to be the next world 
record-holder.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
