<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Pushes Lower Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Republican-led budget plan passed by  
Congress would cut most Americans' taxes while spending more on 
Social Security, education and national defense, GOP Sen. Spencer 
Abraham said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Michigan Republican, delivering the GOP's weekly radio  
address, said the party's agenda ``will help our families and our 
children face the future with optimism and confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The $1.74 trillion spending plan for the fiscal year starting  
Oct. 1 places overall limits on the detailed tax and spending bills 
lawmakers will write, then try to persuade the White House to 
accept. Congress passed the legislation Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tax breaks in the plan are meant to keep Americans from having  
to ``work nearly three hours out of an eight-hour day just to pay 
taxes,'' Abraham said. The GOP plan sets aside for tax cuts $800 
billion of the surplus, which would not be connected to Social 
Security. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the trillions of dollars in surpluses expected in the  
next decade amount to a tax overpayment. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's your money, and Republicans will work to give tax relief  
to as many taxpayers as possible,'' Abraham said. ``We want 
sensible tax cuts for all taxpayers. The president doesn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton wants more closely targeted cuts, largely for lower and  
middle-income Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	Abraham said the GOP budget would preserve for Social Security  
alone the trust fund surplus generated by the nation's retirement 
program. It also would increase education spending by $721 billion 
over the next decade, much more than Clinton proposed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want fewer `Washington knows best' solutions and more  
people at the local level making education decisions for America's 
children,'' Abraham said. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP plan also would rebuild national defense system and  
``give our nation the security it needs in this dangerous world,'' 
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 06:25:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Pays $3.77 Million in Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Gov. George W. Bush said he and his wife  
paid $3.77 million in federal income taxes on an estimated 1998 
income of $18.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wrote a check that is the biggest check I could conceivably  
(write),'' Bush, a possible Republican candidate for the 2000 
presidential election, said Thursday. ``I never dreamt I'd write a 
check that big. Of course, I never dreamt I'd make that much money, 
either.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bushes previously paid $97,252 in taxes.  
</P>
<P>
	The bulk of Bush's 1998 income came from the sale of the Texas  
Rangers baseball team, of which he'd been managing partner before 
his 1994 election as governor. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, who bought into the Rangers for just more than $600,000,  
received about $14.9 million when sale of the club was announced 
last summer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bushes also reported giving $334,425 to churches and  
charitable organizations during 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The blind trust that manages Bush's assets has applied for an  
extension of time to file the governor's 1998 tax returns. It is 
still waiting for tax information from some entities in the trust, 
spokeswoman Karen Hughes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, who established a presidential exploratory campaign on  
March 2, has raised $7.6 million for a possible campaign so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
