<DOCNO> APW19990417.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 13:32:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kentucky's Couch is Top Pick </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Cleveland Browns began the Draft of the  
Quarterbacks today by selecting Kentucky's Tim Couch. 
</P>
<P>
	Couch, who left school after his junior season, reached a  
contract agreement with the expansion team hours before the draft. 
</P>
<P>
	In selecting Couch, the Browns -- awarded a franchise by the NFL  
after the original Browns moved to Baltimore -- opened what was 
expected to be a first-round run on quarterbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Couch posed for photographs with Browns owner Al Lerner while,  
in a makeshift Dawg Pound in the balcony, fans dressed in Browns 
jerseys chanted ``Here we go, Brownies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He displayed so much character and poise,'' Browns president  
Carmen Policy said. ``He's such a solid human being.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Philadelphia continued the fancy with passers by selecting  
Donovan McNabb of Syracuse. McNabb, a three-time Big East Offensive 
Player of Year, joins a team whose projected starting quarterback 
is longtime third-stringer Doug Pederson. 
</P>
<P>
	That didn't meet with the approval of the Eagles fans on hand  
who wanted the team to select Ricky Williams of Texas. For much of 
the hour before the pick, they shouted, ``We want Ricky!'' and they 
booed loudly when McNabb's name was called. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time since 1971, the first three selections were  
quarterbacks after Cincinnati took Akili Smith of Oregon. Although 
Smith was a starter for just one college season, his arm strength 
and athletic ability impressed the Bengals, who already have four 
quarterbacks on their roster. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1971, the top three selections were Jim Plunkett by the  
Patriots, Archie Manning by the Saints and Dan Pastorini by the 
Oilers. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest shock of the draft -- and the biggest surprise in  
many years -- came on the fourth selection. Indianapolis traded star 
running back Marshall Faulk to St. Louis on Thursday, seemingly 
clearing the way to take Heisman Trophy winner Ricky Williams of 
Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Colts instead went for another running back, junior  
Edgerrin James of Miami, whose spectacular performance in the 
season finale against UCLA brought him to prominence. The stunned 
crowd let out a gasp when James' name was announced by commissioner 
Paul Tagliabue. 
</P>
<P>
	``We liked both backs ... but basically we feel Edgerrin gives  
us a little more with what we want to do with our offense,'' Colts 
coach Jim Mora said. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams went with the next pick -- to New Orleans. The Saints,  
who previously offered all of their 1999 picks to Cleveland for the 
top overall spot to get Williams, dealt with Washington moments 
after the Colts' stunner. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Mike Ditka, sporting a big grin and an even bigger cigar  
after selecting college football's career rushing leader, traded a 
first, third, fourth, fifth, sixth and seventh picks this year and 
a first- and third-rounder in 2000 to the Redskins to get Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love the kid. He's what we really need,'' Ditka said. ``He  
gives us what Walter Payton gave us in Chicago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It feels great,'' Williams said. ``I was down there last week,  
and they said, `If we draft you, we can go home and hit the golf 
course.' I'm excited.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rams, looking for a big-play receiver to go with Faulk out  
of the backfield, grabbed Torry Holt of North Carolina State. Then 
Washington jumped right back up to No. 7 overall, sending to 
Chicago the first-rounder acquired from the Saints (12th overall), 
and the third-rounder obtained from New Orleans. The Redskins also 
included their own fourth- and fifth-rounders, plus a third-round 
selection in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Redskins -- and the audience -- caught their breath,  
they selected cornerback-wide receiver-kick returner Champ Bailey 
of Georgia. Bailey was the player Washington hoped to get at the 
No. 5 overall slot, so general manager Charley Casserly showed he 
knows how to play the draft-day-trade game superbly. 
</P>
<P>
	Bailey was the first defensive player selected, although he is  
versatile enough to line up at wideout, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona went for a deep threat to help QB Jake Plummer, taking  
David Boston of Ohio State. Detroit grabbed Chris Claiborne of 
Southern California, rated the top linebacker. Claiborne can play 
inside and out and was the Butkus Award winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris McAlister, whose father James played in the NFL, was taken  
by Baltimore. If the cornerback starts, the Ravens could move Rod 
Woodson to safety. 
</P>
<P>
	A fourth quarterback was selected by Minnesota with the 11th  
overall pick, Daunte Culpepper of Central Florida, who had the 
largest contingent of family and friends on hand. That group roared 
when Culpepper was called. 
</P>
<P>
	Culpepper joins a team that had the best record in the league  
last season but whose starting quarterback, Randall Cunningham, 
turned 36 three weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bears added to the quarterback run by taking left-hander  
Cade McNown of UCLA, whose arm strength has been questioned. 
McNown, who beat out Couch for the All-America team, is a winner, 
though -- several scouts have compared him to Jim McMahon. 
</P>
<P>
	That made for five quarterbacks in the first dozen picks.  
</P>
<P>
	Pittsburgh, desperate for a wideout, might have reached a bit in  
taking Troy Edwards of Louisiana Tech. Edwards had great numbers, 
including 21 passes 405 yards and three touchdowns vs. Nebraska. 
</P>
<P>
	Kansas City, which took tackle Victor Riley a year ago, went for  
another offensive lineman, BYU tackle John Tait. He was the first 
blocker chosen. 
</P>
<P>
	Tampa Bay, which was interested in both Culpepper and McNown,  
settled for defensive tackle Anthony McFarland of LSU, who will 
make a nice sidekick for Warren Sapp. 
</P>
<P>
	Another defensive player, All-American end-linebacker Jevon  
Kearse of Florida, went 16th overall to Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	New England moved up three spots by dealing a third-rounder and  
fifth-rounder to Seattle, along with the 10th overall slot, and 
took a local product, center Damien Woody of Boston College. The 
Patriots lost starter Dave Wohlabaugh as a free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	That began a mini-run on behemoth blockers. Oakland used up  
nearly all of its 15 minutes before choosing All-American tackle 
Matt Stinchcomb of Georgia. The Giants needed only 34 seconds to 
take Notre Dame tackle Luke Petitgout, who was projected to go much 
deeper into the proceedings. 
</P>
<P>
	Seattle traded down again, allowing Dallas to pick Ebenezer  
Ekuban, a defensive end from North Carolina to fill a likely hole 
created by Leon Lett's positive drug test. The Cowboys surrendered 
the 22nd overall pick and a fifth-rounder. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cardinals, who went for excitement earlier, opted for bulk  
in 6-5 1/2, 340-pound L.J. Shelton, a tackle from Eastern Michigan who 
is the son of former NBA player Lonnie Shelton. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Seahawks finally used a first-round pick, it was for  
Lamar King, a defensive end from Division II Saginaw Valley whose 
stock soared after postseason workouts. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bills did as expected, selecting hard-hitting cornerback  
Antoine Winfield of Ohio State. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
