<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jagr Recalls Playing Against Greats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANONSBURG, Pa. (AP) -- The man who may be the NHL's best current  
player is about to go up against the man considered to be the best 
ever. 
</P>
<P>
	But Jaromir Jagr -- a former teammate of Mario Lemieux -- isn't  
ready to give that superlative title to Wayne Gretzky. 
</P>
<P>
	Jagr's Penguins play Gretzky's Rangers Sunday in New York in  
what will be Gretzky's last game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I played with Mario Lemieux and Ron Francis; Mario's in the  
Hall of Fame and Ronnie should be after he retires,'' Jagr said 
Friday. ``And I played against Gretzky, Mark Messier, Ray Bourque 
... guys like that. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me, I think Mario was the best, but Gretzky's a great  
player, too. And that means our game with the Rangers is more 
important for them. It's already important for us to get ready for 
the playoffs,'' Jagr said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins (37-29-14) have two games remaining. They play the  
New York Islanders today at the Civic Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	The playoffs begin Wednesday or Thursday for the Penguins.  
</P>
<P>
	Second-year Penguins coach Kevin Constantine said Gretzky's  
retirement could be a distraction. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been a great player and a great ambassador for the game  
and nobody, including myself, likes to see those people leave it,'' 
Constantine said. ``We love the game ... and Wayne played a big 
part in it, but if he's going to retire, we're honored to be part 
of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the playoffs are more important.  
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to try to get ourselves ready for the playoffs, and  
we'll keep our focus on what we're doing as a team. ... And playing 
a team that has a reason to play helps us better prepare for the 
playoffs,'' Constantine said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers have been successful against the Penguins, with  
three wins and a tie. The Islanders, one of the worst teams in the 
NHL, split four games with Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins need two wins this weekend to rise from the eighth  
playoff spot to the No. 6 position. The Penguins aren't as 
concerned about which team they face in the first round as they are 
about how well they're playing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to be a healthy and rested team going into the  
playoffs, and I think we'll be fine once they start,'' forward 
Matthew Barnaby said. ``So, we're getting things together at the 
right time. 
</P>
<P>
	``Playing the last game against Gretzky will be something to  
tell my grandchildren someday, but we can't get caught up in that. 
We have to get ready for the playoffs and play our own game,'' 
Barnaby said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
