<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tranquility Lake Uupsets Virginie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARCADIA, Calif. (AP) -- Tranquility Lake, ridden by Eddie  
Delahoussaye, used a slow, easy pace to upset unbeaten Virginie and 
win the $250,000 Santa Barbara Handicap by four lengths Saturday at 
Santa Anita Park. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Tranquility Lake's first stakes victory.  
</P>
<P>
	Virginie finished second, 1 1/4 lengths in front of Midnight Line  
in the field of seven in the Grade II turf handicap for fillies and 
mares 4-years-old and up. Virginie had eight wins in her native 
Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	Tranquility Lake set the pace and never relinquished it, leading  
by five lengths at the three-quarter mark. The winner covered 1 1/4 
miles over a firm course in 2:01, earning $150,000 and increasing 
her career earnings to $349,100. 
</P>
<P>
	Tranquility Lake carried 116 pounds and paid $13.40, $6.60 and  
$4.60. Virginie returned $4 and $3.20, while Midnight Line paid 
$4.40 to show. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even if there had been pace in front of her, she could have  
sat right off it and won,'' Delahoussaye said. ``When I found 
myself alone on the lead, I said, `Hey, we're on our way.''' 
</P>
<P>
	It was Tranquility Lake's fourth win in 11 starts.  
</P>
<P>
	In the $108,700 San Simeon Handicap, 11-1 long shot Naninja,  
ridden by Chris McCarron, won by a neck. The 6-year-old gelding 
covered 6 1/2 furlongs over a firm turf course in 1:13 1-5 and won 
$65,220 for lifetime earnings of $289,940. 
</P>
<P>
	Expressionist finished second, a head in front of favored Indian  
Rocket in the field of seven in the Grade III handicap for 
4-year-olds and up. 
</P>
<P>
	Naninja, carried 115 pounds and paid $25.20, $9.60 and $3.80.  
Expressionist returned $4.60 and $2.80, while Indian Rocket was 
$2.40 to show. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 12:22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Starr May Turn Over Part of Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Kenneth Starr is raising the possibility he  
might turn over parts of his criminal investigation of the Clintons 
to the Justice Department when the independent counsel law expires 
June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	If the law is not renewed, an independent counsel is required to  
``make a determination as to whether his continuation with matters 
in his jurisdiction is required,'' Starr said in an interview 
Friday with The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr said he would follow the law and consult with the Justice  
Department before deciding. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecutor, whose investigation of almost five years has  
been criticized widely, said one possible approach would be to make 
``judgments ... with respect to what matters the independent 
counsel should carry on'' with ``and what matters should be 
otherwise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rejecting a suggestion he is readying an exit strategy, Starr  
said his office will continue to function, though he declined to 
say how long he plans to stay on the job. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr said he is considering replacing three Washington deputies  
who departed recently. ``We may be having an announcement'' 
shortly, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	At least for now, Congress seems unlikely to reauthorize the  
post-Watergate statue. But a clause in the law says existing 
counsels are to stay on the job until their investigation is 
complete. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr refused to speculate about what parts of his investigation  
might be turned over to the Justice Department, with which Starr 
said relations have become ``especially difficult'' in the past 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Monica Lewinsky investigation, the department represented  
the Secret Service in the court battle to keep uniformed officers 
and agents from testifying in Starr's investigation. Starr won the 
fight. 
</P>
<P>
	The department has advised Starr it intends to investigate his  
handling of the Lewinsky affair. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr said he has enjoyed the ``unfailing support of the  
director of the FBI. Louis Freeh has been terrific.'' Asked whether 
he would apply a similar assessment to the Attorney General Janet 
Reno, Starr declined comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Relations with the Justice Department were excellent in 1994  
when he began investigating the president and first lady Hillary 
Rodham Clinton for their involvement in the Whitewater real venture 
in Arkansas, Starr said. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, Starr noted prosecutors got prompt approval from  
Reno to investigate then-Arkansas Gov. Jim Guy Tucker's cable 
television business, which had made him wealthy. Tucker ultimately 
pleaded guilty to using a sham bankruptcy to avoid taxes on that 
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr said cooperation from the attorney general is essential  
for the law to work properly. 
</P>
<P>
	The law ``purports to regulate with precision the attorney  
general's exercise of discretion, but then leads her exercise of 
discretion completely unreviewed and unchecked,'' Starr said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still pending before Starr's office are:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Two trials involving longtime Clinton friend and former  
associate attorney general Webster Hubbell. One is for tax evasion; 
the other for concealing evidence. Both cases are delayed because 
of appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	-- A decision on whether to seek a retrial of Susan McDougal, one  
of the Clintons' Whitewater partners, on two counts of criminal 
contempt for refusing to give grand jury testimony about the 
president and first lady in 1996 and 1998. A judge declared a 
mistrial on the two counts Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	-- A May 3 trial of a Virginia woman, Julie Hiatt Steele, in  
Alexandria, Va., charged with obstructing Starr's probe into 
whether Clinton made an unwanted sexual advance toward former White 
House volunteer Kathleen Willey. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Wrapping up investigations of the FBI files controversy and  
the White House travel office firings. 
</P>
<P>
	One former independent counsel, Iran-Contra prosecutor Lawrence  
Walsh, said he did not think ``the expiration of the law is the 
test'' for sending a matter to the Justice Department. 
</P>
<P>
	``The test is whether there's a conflict of interest that  
prevents you from turning it back to Justice,'' Walsh said. 
</P>
<P>
	Walsh served the final part of his tenure after the independent  
counsel law had expired the last time, in December 1992. He wrote 
his final report in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The law was reauthorized in June 1994, with Clinton's support.  
</P>
<P>
	A former Iran-Contra prosecutor on Walsh's staff, John Barrett,  
said there is nothing in the independent counsel law that requires 
Starr ``to terminate any aspect of his activity after June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	``The law explicitly grandfathers in Independent Counsels as  
Walsh was grandfathered when the law expired in December of 1992,'' 
said Barrett, a St. John's University law professor. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Starr surprised many by testifying before Congress  
that that law is flawed and should not be renewed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I opposed the law back in the early 1980s when serving as  
chief of staff to then-Attorney General William French Smith,'' 
Starr said in the interview. ``My views have developed over the 
years, but they have not changed.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
