<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 14:42:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> USOC Tells Salt Lake to Cool It </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Olympic organizers must step away from  
politics and stop worrying about money, says the top fundraising 
official for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am calling for an end to political rhetoric,'' said John  
Krimsky, deputy secretary general for the U.S. Olympic Committee. 
``The organizing committee is being led to an extent by those who 
have a government agenda ... (SLOC) cannot become distracted by 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Krimsky said there's too much attention being paid to the  
possibility taxpayers could be responsible if organizers can't 
cover the $1.4 billion budget. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said he's concerned sponsors will be driven away by  
extensive discussion of the Salt Lake bribery scandal's impact on 
finances. Companies don't want to be associated with a financially 
troubled Olympics any more than they want to see their names next 
to news of the scandal, Krimsky said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't chill the sales and marketing agreement and drive  
sponsors away because they feel these will not be the best games 
ever -- for whatever reason,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Krimsky is leading a marketing effort set on raising $859  
million from corporate sponsors. He said he's confident the money 
is there even though no new sponsors have signed on since the 
scandal surfaced last year, because four deals are pending, 
including one with the automobile manufacturer BMW. 
</P>
<P>
	About a dozen companies like US WEST, Delta Air Lines and  
Anheuser-Busch already have paid $50 million or so in cash, goods 
and services to sponsor both the Games and the U.S. Olympic teams 
through 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	SLOC's share of the cash expected to be raised through the joint  
sponsorship program is about $250 million. SLOC President Mitt 
Romney has pledged to raise $100 million from Utah residents. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, Krimsky said, organizers should stop mulling over the  
numbers and start preparing for the games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We seem to be preoccupied with the budget at the moment. I  
hope nothing is falling through the cracks,'' he said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
