<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> HIV-Infected Mom Fights for Baby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EUGENE, Ore. (AP) -- An HIV-infected woman who insists on her  
right to breast-feed is taking a life-or-death chance with her 
child, a state attorney said during a custody hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Kathleen Tyson is ``playing Russian roulette with the virus,''  
said Robert Nagler, the state lawyer who is representing 
4-month-old Felix Tyson in court proceedings that began Friday. 
``The parents were blessed with a robust, healthy child, but they 
also chose to adopt a cause.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tyson and her husband, David, have physical custody of the  
child, but the state has retained legal custody pending the outcome 
of the hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for the couple promised Friday to call witnesses who  
believe there is no evidence that the HIV virus can be contracted 
by drinking breast milk, and who do not believe the HIV virus 
causes AIDS. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tysons ascribe to both theories and argue that they have the  
right to raise Felix as they see fit. 
</P>
<P>
	``She made a choice that she feels is in Felix's best  
interest,'' said Hilary Billings, the mother's attorney. ``It's a 
measure of risks against each other and benefits against each other 
... The issue would boil down to where a certain line needs to be 
drawn.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Tysons are part of the ``Rethinking AIDS'' movement led by  
scientist David Rasnick of the University of California at 
Berkeley. Rasnick is expected to testify that there is no 
relationship between HIV and AIDS, and that the state has no right 
to enforce unfounded medical theory. 
</P>
<P>
	But sentiments on the other side are equally strong. A number of  
medical professionals and social workers believe Felix's health 
would be endangered if he were to drink his mother's milk. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's bizarre that 18 years after the epidemic began that  
there's any question about the cause of HIV infection,'' said 
Leslie Mehlhaff, an infectious disease specialist who advised Tyson 
against breast feeding. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours after Felix was born Dec. 7, a state social worker arrived  
at the hospital with three uniformed police officers after Tyson's 
doctor expressed concern about her breast-feeding the baby. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Jo Driscoll, social worker with Oregon's child welfare  
agency, said the couple became combative and told her they believed 
bottle feeding was the method that carried the real deadly risks. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were upset,'' she said. ``They believed they were making  
informed decisions about their son. They thought I was intruding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several weeks after the state took legal custody of Felix, he  
tested negative for HIV. He has not been tested since. 
</P>
<P>
	About once a week, a caseworker from Oregon's Office for  
Services to Children and Families makes a visit to the Tyson home 
to ensure the state's will is being carried out. The caseworker 
said the child shows no sign of behavior typical of breast-feeding 
and Tyson can be trusted to carry out the court order. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
