<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clash 2, United 1, SO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Raul Diaz Arce's goal in the fifth shootout  
round gave the San Jose Clash a 2-1 victory over D.C. United on 
Saturday night before the largest crowd to watch a regular-season 
MLS game at RFK Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Diaz Arce challenged United goalkeeper Tom Presthus straight on,  
sliding a low shot that snuck beneath his right arm for the 
decisive goal. 
</P>
<P>
	San Jose also got goals during the shootout from Ronald  
Cerritos, Eddie Lewis and Jamie Clark. 
</P>
<P>
	Marco Etcheverry and Jaime Moreno scored in the first two rounds  
of the shootout for D.C. United, which lost its first in four 
starts. 
</P>
<P>
	The game drew 35,167, the largest crowd to see an MLS regular  
season game, surpassing the 35,032 that attended D.C. United's 
inaugural match in 1996. The only larger crowd in franchise history 
was the 57,431 that saw the United win the MLS Cup in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	D.C. United's Geoff Augner and Cerritos swapped goals in a  
seven-minute, first-half span for a 1-1 halftime tie. 
</P>
<P>
	The United went ahead 1-0 in the fourth minute when Augner  
converted a left-wing chip from Etcheverry. 
</P>
<P>
	Presthus gobbled up Diaz Arce's point-blank attempt about a  
minute later, but was helpless to stop Cerritos in the 11th minute. 
Cerritos leaped high to flick a header off a feed from Cloutier. 
</P>
<P>
	Augner was ejected in the 75th minute for undercutting San  
Jose's Jeff Baicher, and the United played a man down for the 
remainder of regulation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
