<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Results of Pew Gore Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Some results from a poll by the Pew Research Center for the  
People &AMP; the Press on Vice President Al Gore, the presidential race 
and problems with the Clinton administration. When results don't 
total 100 percent, the remainder either did not know or had no 
answer. 

</P>
<P>
	--Would you say your overall opinion of Al Gore is very  
favorable, mostly favorable, mostly unfavorable or very 
unfavorable? 
</P>
<P>
	Very favorable, 12 percent; mostly favorable, 35 percent; mostly  
unfavorable, 26 percent; very unfavorable, 17 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time Gore's favorable rating had dipped below 50  
percent was in September 1997, when he was at the center of a 
campaign fund-raising scandal. 

</P>
<P>
	--As of today, do you lean more to Gore, the Democrat, or Bush,  
the Republican? 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, 41 percent; Bush, 54 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	Gore trailed Bush by 6 points in a Pew poll in January.  

</P>
<P>
	--As of today, do you lean more to Gore, the Democrat, or Dole,  
the Republican? 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, 42 percent; Dole, 52 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	Gore trailed Dole by 4 points in a Pew poll in January.  

</P>
<P>
	--Do you agree or disagree with this statement: I am tired of all  
the problems associated with the Clinton administration? 
</P>
<P>
	Agree, 74 percent; disagree 23 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	About that many independents agreed with the statement, and  
almost two-thirds of those who felt that way favored Bush over Gore 
for president. 

</P>
<P>
	The poll of 1,786 adults was taken March 24-30 and has an error  
margin of plus or minus 3 percentage points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
