<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Patriots Get The Big Kat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- Andy Katzenmoyer might be known best for  
being one of Ohio State's greatest linebackers if he wasn't known 
nearly as well for academic and alcohol problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The New England Patriots overlooked those troubles -- and the  
fact his play dropped off last season -- and took him with the 28th 
pick of the first round of Saturday's NFL draft, their second 
choice of the day. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's going to bring great enthusiasm and intensity,'' Patriots  
coach Pete Carroll said. ``He's as fast as any linebacker out 
there. He's big and strong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Katzenmoyer was a second-team All-American as a freshman in  
1996, a first-team All-American in 1997 but only a first-team 
All-Big Ten conference selection last season as a junior. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did the jobs that the coaches asked me to do,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	His coach, John Cooper, said opponents put two and three  
blockers on him to try to control him last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The other teams wised up a little bit,'' Cooper said. ``I  
thought Andy would go in the top 10 (or 15) this year. Physically, 
he's got that kind of talent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a first-round draft pick,'' Katzenmoyer said. ``That's  
something that every kid dreams of, and I'm going to a great 
organization so there's nothing to complain about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His problems might have hurt his stock in the draft, Cooper  
said. And Katzenmoyer admitted he let his schoolwork slip to the 
point where he had to go to summer school before last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just lack of discipline on my part in the grades  
department. I was lost for a little while and my classes slipped,'' 
he said. ``It just woke me up and made me realize you can't fall 
behind in anything you want to achieve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said his past alcohol problems are ``a non-issue with me and  
my family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was convicted of underage drinking after a policeman saw him  
with a beer at a bar on his Ohio State recruiting visit. And last 
winter, he pleaded no contest to charges of speeding and drunken 
driving. He paid fines in both cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Carroll didn't seem particularly concerned.  
</P>
<P>
	``When we start talking about Andy ... being kind of crazy and  
kind of wild and a guy that isn't real fired up about school, it 
kind of starts making a little format for what a linebacker might 
be all about that you need in this league,'' Carroll said. ``This 
guy is nuts about football. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's really excited about the fact that now he can concentrate  
and put all his direction into football.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Katzenmoyer was an inside linebacker in college, but the  
Patriots plan to use him outside as a replacement for Todd Collins, 
who signed with St. Louis as a free agent. Katzenmoyer could share 
time at that spot with Tedy Bruschi, who is best in third-down 
situations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
