<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crew 1, Revolution 0, SO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- New England player-coach Walter Zenga made  
a handful of brilliant saves in regulation but allowed four goals 
in the shootout as the Columbus Crew beat the Revolution 1-0 
Saturday night in the MLS. 
</P>
<P>
	Stern John, Brian McBride, Jeff Cunningham and Jason Farrell all  
scored in the shootout for Columbus (3-1), while Kris Kelderman 
converted the lone goal for the Revolution (1-3). 
</P>
<P>
	Three of New England's four matches this season have been  
decided by a shootout, prompting the crowd to chant ``No more 
shootouts'' prior to the shootout. 
</P>
<P>
	The game, played at a breakneck pace with little imagination or  
control by either side, was punctuated by missed scoring chances. 
</P>
<P>
	The Crew had the better of the play, but missed two easy chances  
in the opening minutes and a handful of golden opportunities later 
on. 
</P>
<P>
	John, a Trinidad &AMP; Tobago international, failed to finish in the  
first minute of play and then was foiled by a masterful goalkeeping 
demonstration by Zenga. After Zenga kicked out a bid by McBride, he 
snuffed a 6-yard blast from John at 36 minutes and a minute later, 
stopped a shot by John from 14 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	The Revolution failed to create more than a couple of legitimate  
chances. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 53rd minute, Edwin Gorter threaded a pass to Johnny  
Torres, whose shot from 12 yards was headed off the line by Crew 
midfielder Todd Yeagley. Six minutes later, the Revolution nearly 
scored when Joe-Max Moore was put through by Tony Kuhn only to 
shoot wide along the left post from 16 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	At 69 minutes, John headed down a cross from substitute Ansil  
Elcock only to have McBride put the ball over the bar from seven 
yards. 
</P>
<P>
	The Crew in the midst of seven straight road games as they await  
the completion of their new, soccer-specific stadium, are 10-3 
all-time against New England. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
