<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 13:42:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Skins Swap Around, Still Get Bailey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASHBURN, Va. (AP) -- The Washington Redskins worked the draft to  
perfection, wheeling and dealing and winding up with exactly what 
they wanted -- and more. 
</P>
<P>
	After two trades involving 11 draft picks in the first 90  
minutes Saturday, the Redskins not only got the player they had 
targeted -- Georgia cornerback Champ Bailey -- but also left 
themselves loaded for next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Surprised to see Heisman Trophy winner Ricky Williams still  
available when they went on the clock, the Redskins took up Mike 
Ditka's offer and traded their No. 5 overall pick for the New 
Orleans Saints' entire draft -- plus first- and third-round choices 
next year. 
</P>
<P>
	That put the Redskins at No. 12 overall, too low to get Bailey,  
so they packaged five picks and sent them to Chicago to move up to 
No. 7. 
</P>
<P>
	The end result: Bailey comes to Washington, and the Redskins --  
who already had two first-round draft picks in 2000 -- now have 
three. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're talking about a lot of phone calls in a short period of  
time,'' said general manager Charley Casserly, who had worked out a 
firm deal with New Orleans and a tentative one with Chicago before 
the draft started just in the unlikely case that Williams didn't go 
in the top four. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone felt at No. 4, Indianapolis was going to take a  
running back. Everyone assumed it was Ricky Williams. We were 
wrong,'' Casserly said. ``So we moved back two spots, got a No. 1 
next year and the player we were going to take at No. 5. When we 
put that all together, it's a pretty good deal for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Casserly said the Redskins gave some consideration to taking  
Williams, but coach Norv Turner is content with young running backs 
Stephen Davis and Skip Hicks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal was to come away with a corner,'' Turner said.  
``Champ Bailey was the corner we preferred.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bailey, 6-foot and 181 pounds, was considered the best  
all-around player available in the draft. He was also a stellar 
receiver and return man in college, but Turner said he wants Bailey 
to concentrate on defense before even trying to make him the next 
Deion Sanders. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest thing for Champ is to come in here and learn how  
to play cornerback at this level,'' Turner said. ``With specific 
coaching, spending all of his time on defense, he can make great 
strides and improve. We're not going to fool around with the 
offensive part of it until he's thoroughly comfortable as a 
corner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Turner said he expects Bailey to start this season, and backed  
it up by announcing that 11-year veteran and two-time Pro Bowl 
selection Cris Dishman -- who had a miserable season last year -- 
will be released Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	That news stunned Bailey.  
</P>
<P>
	``Oh, man,'' Bailey said. ``I remember watching him when he  
played for the Oilers, and he was a great corner. That's as big 
complement. Man! Oh, that means a lot right there. For them to do 
that, that means they got a lot of confidence in me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bailey, speaking by phone from his family home in Folkston, Ga.,  
said he was celebrating his selection with about 300 people and an 
outdoor buffet of crawfish. 
</P>
<P>
	As far as Turner's decree that can't play offense right away,  
Bailey sounded eager to prove he can go both ways in the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can prove myself to be a great corner, and playing other  
positions can only help me, I believe,'' Bailey said. ``I'm going 
to be ready to do whatever it takes to prove myself at this level 
and do what I've got to do be a productive corner and receiver.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 12:32:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pit Road Could Decide Goody's 500 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARTINSVILLE, Va. (AP) -- Now that they've all had a chance to  
see Martinsville Speedway's all-new pit road, some Winston Cup 
drivers think it's an equalizer while others see it as a travesty 
waiting to happen. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of pits on the front and back stretches, the .526-mile  
oval now has one long pit road that begins where the third turn 
starts, continues all the way through the front stretch and stops 
where the second turn ends. 
</P>
<P>
	Drivers have long complained at NASCAR's oldest and shortest  
track that pitting on the back under the old setup made winning 
near impossible, but many view the new arrangement with a 35 
mph-pit road speed as dicey, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to be careful what you pray for sometimes,'' said  
Darrell Waltrip, second only to Richard Petty with 11 career 
victories at Martinsville Speedway. ``We've all been praying for 
one pit road here and we've got it. Now we've got to help them make 
it as good as it can be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kyle Petty, who qualified 10th for Sunday's Goody's Body Pain  
500, doesn't like it at all, saying he preferred the front and back 
pits. 
</P>
<P>
	``The pit road is going to kill you, period, on a green-flag  
stop,'' he said. ``Look at the race track. It's a half-mile track. 
We can get around here in 20 seconds. It takes you 44 seconds to go 
down pit road at 35 mph. That's two laps you've got already during 
a green flag stop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Petty said he didn't mind pitting on the back and at least  
having a chance to be competitive, but Winston Cup point standings 
leader Jeff Burton thinks the difference between competing and 
having a chance matters. 
</P>
<P>
	``You may be penalized because you're running in the back, but  
in Winston Cup racing we get paid points for racing,'' said Burton, 
who qualified third. ``The only thing that pays in qualifying is 
the pole. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything around Winston Cup is built on racing, so why  
should there be a pit road on the back that hampers you from 
winning that badly?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The wall erected to form the outside boundary of pit road also  
gives some drivers cause for concern, some saying the road isn't 
wide enough, especially at the end in turns one and two, others 
because it's something to hit. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only problem will be if somebody spins and backs up in  
(the turns),'' Waltrip said. ``There no grass to back into. There's 
a wall.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several drivers said they planned to watch Saturday's NAPA 250  
Craftsman Truck Series race with interest to see how the pit 
situation worked out, and others said they were content just to see 
what happens on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no telling what we're going to see,'' Ken Schrader  
said. ``I wouldn't even start to guess about that. It's going to be 
interesting.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 14:12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
