<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Misplaced Embryo Case Explored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An embryologist who assisted in the in vitro  
fertilization of a woman who gave birth to two babies -- one white, 
one black -- knew his error caused the wrong embryo to be implanted 
in the woman but remained silent, according to a state inquiry. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Obasaju was aware he had given Dr. Lillian Nash the  
wrong embryos for implantation but prepared a second batch with 
correct embryos rather than stop the procedure immediately, 
according to the report, which was obtained under the Freedom of 
Information Act and detailed in today's New York Times. 
</P>
<P>
	The case that became public last month when Robert Rogers and  
Deborah Perry-Rogers, a black couple from Teaneck, N.J., claimed 
Richard and Donna Fasano, who are both white, were given an embryo 
that the Rogers stored at the IVF New York clinic in Manhattan. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Fasano gave birth to two boys in December 1998. One child,  
who is white, was her biological child; the black baby is no 
relation. 
</P>
<P>
	The mix-up occurred on April 24, 1998, when Mrs. Fasano and Mrs.  
Perry-Rogers were in the office for embryo implantation after in 
vitro fertilization of their eggs. 
</P>
<P>
	In preparing the embryos, Obasaju separated four of Mrs.  
Perry-Rogers' fertilized embryos, which he determined to be lower 
grade, to be discarded. But he accidentally placed those embryos 
into a catheter used for Mrs. Fasano's procedure, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Had he announced his mistake immediately, the embryos could have  
been washed out, said Diane Mathis, a state Department of Health 
spokeswoman. But Obasaju didn't admit his error until Nash learned 
that Mrs. Fasano was pregnant, the report said. He did not come 
forward sooner because he thought the wrong embryos would not grow, 
it said. 
</P>
<P>
	The state report cited Nash for failing to properly oversee  
Obasaju. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fasanos filed a malpractice suit against Nash, Obasaju and  
another physician, Dr. Dov Goldstein, on April 5. Court papers said 
Nash informed both couples of the mistake months before Mrs. Fasano 
gave birth to the boy. The Fasanos did not know the Rogers until 
they filed suit seeking custody of the black baby. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fasanos have said they will give the Rogers custody of the  
black baby if DNA tests show they are the baby's genetic parents. 
</P>
<P>
	David Cohen, a lawyer for the Fasanos, said Friday that the  
tests had been completed. He would not reveal the results, but said 
lawyers for both couples were negotiating a visitation agreement so 
the boys would grow up knowing each other. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 13:06:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Gore Speaks of Balkans Link </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Recalling an uncle who suffered poison  
gas exposure in World War I, Vice President Al Gore said his family 
is ``one of millions that knows firsthand'' about the Balkans' role 
in world stability. 
</P>
<P>
	``Will the 21st century be shaped and molded by thugs in ski  
masks with weapons in their hands and hatred in their hearts? The 
answer given by the people of the United States of America is no,'' 
Gore said Friday night at his first Tennessee fund-raiser for the 
2000 presidential election. 
</P>
<P>
	``We saw midway through this century the moral consequences of  
crimes against humanity that occurred with much of the world 
standing by, not doing much of anything about it,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking to about 450 Democratic supporters gathered at a  
$1,000-per-plate dinner, Gore promised to get Kosovar refugees 
``back to their homes, with security and with justice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore is expected to spend this weekend campaigning in New  
Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore hasn't officially announced his campaign for the 2000  
Democratic nomination, but has raised $8.9 million, according to 
the Federal Election Commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
