<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Serbs Told to Halt Policy  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO's commander bluntly told  
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic today to change his policies 
in Kosovo or see his military machine destroyed. Meanwhile, NATO 
began its 25th night of bombing. NATO disclosed today what it said 
was more proof of atrocities by Serb forces in Kosovo, showing 
reporters aerial photos of what it claimed may be up to 150 fresh 
graves near the Kosovo town of Izbica. ``It's clear that there is 
mounting evidence of detentions, summary executions and mass 
graves,'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea told reporters in Brussels, 
Belgium. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S., Yugoslavia Won't Trade POWs  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It appears there is no interest in either  
Washington or Belgrade to trade prisoners of war captured since 
NATO began its bombing campaign. So U.S. military leaders are 
continuing to mull what to do with a Yugoslav prisoner of war, 
while remaining concerned about three American soldiers seized near 
the Macedonian border two weeks ago. Trading the captured Yugoslav 
officer would be a politically tricky equation, Defense officials 
said on condition of anonymity. On one hand, they said, release of 
the three Americans would be a relief, but it would carry the risk 
of equating what the United States calls an abduction of 
peacekeeping soldiers with the capture of a bona fide enemy POW. 

</P>
<P>
	Dozens Injured in London Blast  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- An explosion fired nails through a crowded street  
market in south London today, injuring dozens. Witnesses said the 
blast was caused by a bomb. No deaths were reported, but Scotland 
Yard said people had been seriously injured in the explosion at 
5:25 p.m. local time. A trader at the market said he had seen the 
device before it exploded. He said nails were stuck on it with 
transparent tape. Police said they received reports of at least 48 
people injured, although apparently not all sought hospital 
treatment. 

</P>
<P>
	US Destroyer Bears Churchill's Name  
</P>
<P>
	BATH, Maine (AP) -- A U.S. Navy destroyer was launched today  
bearing the name of former British prime minister Sir Winston 
Churchill -- an honor rarely afforded foreigners. Lady Soames, the 
former British leader's only living child, joined U.S. Defense 
Secretary William Cohen, British Defense Minister George Robertson 
and other Churchill relatives to watch the 505-foot warship Winston 
S. Churchill slide down a greased ramp at the Bath Iron Works into 
the Kennebec River. Cohen said Churchill ``gave the world hope in 
the darkest hours and helped shape the world that we know today.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Hurt by Clinton, Poll Says  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore's work to gain support  
for his presidential campaign may be hindered by his close 
association to President Clinton, a poll released today is 
indicating. Public weariness with the Clinton administration's 
ethical problems may be what is taking a toll on Gore's campaign. 
For the first time since September 1997, when Gore was at the 
center of a controversy about campaign fund-raising, his favorable 
ratings slipped below 50 percent in the poll by the Pew Research 
Center for the People &AMP; the Press. 

</P>
<P>
	India Govt. Resigns After Vote  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- India's Hindu nationalist government  
resigned today after losing a confidence vote by a single ballot, a 
margin that signaled continued political turmoil as Italian-born 
Sonia Gandhi prepared to try to form the next government. The 
270-269 vote ended the 13-month administration of the Hindu 
nationalist government, which unveiled India's nuclear weapons 
capability to the world, prompting rival Pakistan to follow suit. 

</P>
<P>
	Jordan King, Arafat Meet Gadhafi  
</P>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and  
Jordan's King Abdullah visited Libya today to seek Moammar 
Gadhafi's support on separate issues. Gadhafi met with Abdullah and 
Arafat, Libyan television said. They discussed Arab and 
international issues, the broadcast said without giving details. 
Egypt's official Middle East News Agency said the talks focused on 
the stalled Mideast peace process and efforts to unite Arab 
nations. 

</P>
<P>
	Rockies Beat Braves, 5-4  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Darryl Hamilton's RBI single off John Rocker  
capped a three-run ninth inning as the Colorado Rockies rallied to 
beat the Atlanta Braves 5-4 today. Pinch-hitter Angel Echevarria 
tied the game with a one-out single that scored Todd Helton and 
Mike Lansing. Hamilton followed with a soft line drive to 
left-center, and Pat Watkins scored just ahead of the throw from 
center fielder Andruw Jones. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
