<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kyle Petty Has Brush With a Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARTINSVILLE, Va. (AP) -- Kyle Petty's first pole of the year  
wasn't at all like he hoped it would be. It came a week early at 
Talladega. 
</P>
<P>
	While testing for next weekend's stop on the Winston Cup circuit  
Wednesday, Petty's car spun out of control and through a chain-link 
fence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I ran through the chain-link fence and over a couple of  
azaleas, and I think a couple of dandelions gave their lives,'' 
Petty said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just a freak deal. I've never had anything happen like  
that. Never. I hit the curb and the concrete around the flagpole 
and the thing jumped up in the air about two or three feet and 
nailed the flagpole.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The flagpole finally stopped Petty's Pontiac, the same car he  
finished seventh in at Daytona, and the one he still plans to race 
in next Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It needed a new front snout and really, everything forward  
from the front firewall. I just got out and laughed,'' he said. 
``In hindsight, I was thankful. If it had been during practice, I 
would have hit some people.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *NO FAN OF BULLRINGS:* Ken Schrader will start sixth in the  
Goody's 500, and he'll be looking to better his previous best 
finish here, a fourth in 1988. But don't count Schrader among 
Winston Cup's short-track fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a different weekend,'' he said of the race on the  
.526-mile oval. ``We'll see a lot of car wrestling. They just beat 
and bang.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three of Schrader's four career victories have come on tracks of  
at least 1 1/2 miles, the last at the mile-long track at Dover in 
1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinsville, though, isn't his favorite stop on the circuit.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a decent track for us, but I don't like the short  
tracks,'' he said. ``I could do this all the time, and this isn't 
why I went Winston Cup racing, to go beat around on the half-miles, 
but it's part of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SECOND ROUND:* Dick Trickle was the only one of 10 drivers who  
attempted to requalify Saturday to improve his speed and gain a 
spot in the top 36. Trickle's speed was 93.854 mph after a 
first-round best of 93.631 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	The drivers who didn't make the race were Dave Marcis, Morgan  
Shepherd and Buckshot Jones. Marcis and Shepherd have missed four 
of eight races. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *HAPPY BIRTHDAY?:* The Goody's 500 will be run on Geoff Bodine's  
50th birthday at the site of his first career victory back in 1984. 
Bodine has won three others times here, and wants to have a party 
on the track Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bodine has won 18 Winston Cup races, but none since Watkins Glen  
in 1996. The Goody's race will be his 80th since the last victory, 
and Bodine thinks it would be nice if his fellow drivers would help 
him mark the day right. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everyone should just move over and let me win the  
race.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *STATS 'N STUFF:* The Goody's 500 will be Ernie Irvan's 300th  
career Winston Cup start. ... Fords have won only 12 times at 
Martinsville in the 54 modern era races since 1972. All 12 
victories have come since 1986. ... Rusty Wallace's victory in the 
Food City 500 at Bristol last weekend made him the seventh winner 
in the last seven Winston Cup short-track races. 
</P>
</TEXT>
