<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ayala Looks Forward to Boxing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- About a year ago, 36-year-old Tony Ayala started  
thinking seriously about fighting again. 
</P>
<P>
	Fighting -- it's what Ayala did with a skill that excited boxing  
insiders and a fury that brought roaring mobs to their feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Fighting -- it's something Ayala hasn't done since he was 19,  
when he compiled a 22-0 record, with 19 knockouts as a junior 
middleweight. He was on the verge of superstardom. 
</P>
<P>
	Out of the ring, Ayala was a problem.  
</P>
<P>
	``When I was 19, I was a junky and a drunk, I was out of  
control,'' Ayala said in a telephone interview from Bayside State 
Prison in Leesburg, N.J. On Tuesday, he'll be released after 
serving 16 years of a 35-year sentence for rape. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early morning hours of New Year's Day 1983, Ayala  
returned to his Paterson, N.J., home after a night out with 
common-law wife, Lisa Paez. She went to bed. He said he was going 
to watch television. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, stoked by heroin and booze, he went to the home of a  
female neighbor and raped her. At the time, he was on probation for 
beating a woman in the restroom of a San Antonio drive-in theater 
in 1980, and for breaking into a San Antonio home in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	``Did I deserve to go to prison?'' Ayala asked, repeating a  
question. ``Damn right. Did I deserve to go to prison for 16 years? 
That's another matter. The last 10 years were a waste of time and 
money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ayala started thinking about a comeback three years ago. Last  
year, he made up his mind to do it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going into it blind,'' he said. ``I know the odds are  
against me. What people don't see is the heart, the desire. I think 
I still have enough to fulfill my destiny, or at least give it a 
shot. Another big factor is the financial reward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ayala's story of a promising career derailed is salable, at  
least for a few fights. But to try to recreate ``The Little Bull,'' 
who could have been great at one time, seems beyond reach. 
</P>
<P>
	He says he weighs 175 pounds, but would like to fight again as a  
junior middleweight. To do so he must lose 21 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	While boxing again is Ayala's hope, there were a few years when  
he had wiped it out of his mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first five or six years of prison, I never thought of  
boxing,'' said Ayala, who served five years in Trenton and nine in 
Rahway before being transferred Bayside. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was another life. I was totally focused on fixing what  
was broken inside myself. It was just common sense,'' he said. ``I 
was in prison, not for boxing. I was in prison because I committed 
a horrible crime. 
</P>
<P>
	``Also, a lot of my attention was on not getting killed. I had  
some close calls. Thankfully, I had a guardian angel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ayala said he has the support of his family, including Lisa, who  
left him, but has since come back. There also is Dr. Brian Raditz, 
a psychologist who treated Ayala his first 4 1/2 years in prison and 
became his friend. Raditz will serve as Ayala's adviser. His 
father, Tony Sr., again will train his son. 
</P>
<P>
	``I gained spirituality, focus and discipline in prison,'' Ayala  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But he also questioned the system's value as a rehabilitation  
tool. 
</P>
<P>
	``Politicians make a career out of bashing prisoners,'' he said.  
``I'm saying they put a person in prison, dehumanize him, take his 
heart, then after 15 or 20 years they release him and expect him to 
act like a regular person.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's not too late for Ayala to become a regular person, but  
there has to be considerable doubt he can again become a special 
fighter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 09:22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyans Dominate Boston Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- To John Kagwe, the dominance of Kenyan runners at  
the Boston Marathon is similar to the hold the United States has on 
basketball with its Dream Team lineups. 
</P>
<P>
	Winners make more winners.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's like Michael Jordan in basketball,'' said Kagwe, a  
two-time New York City Marathon champion and one of nine elite 
Kenyan runners in Monday's field. ``The younger ones see how well 
John Kagwe is doing and they want to be like him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before we came, there were difficulties. There were Kenyans  
who tried but couldn't make it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lately, they've been making it every time they take to the  
course. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending champion Moses Tanui, No. 2 Joseph Chebet and Kagwe  
will lead the charge for a record-tying ninth consecutive Kenyan 
title in the world's most prestigious marathon. 
</P>
<P>
	The top-flight women's field is led by two-time defending  
champion Fatuma Roba of Ethiopia, the 1996 Olympic gold medalist, 
and includes Lynn Jennings, the top American woman distance runner 
who is making her official marathon debut. 
</P>
<P>
	Also running is Bill Rodgers, the four-time Boston winner who is  
aiming for an American over-50 course record at age 51. 
</P>
<P>
	Keith Brantly, a 1996 American Olympic marathoner, calls the  
current crop of Kenyans ``the best distance runners the world has 
ever seen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The way the Kenyans are performing these days, there's little  
argument. 
</P>
<P>
	Tanui, who also won the centennial Boston race in 1996, took  
last year's edition in a career-best 2 hours, 7 minutes, 34 
seconds. Chebet was runner-up to Tanui last year at 2:07:37 and the 
second-place finisher in the past two New York City Marathons. 
Kagwe has a career-best 2:08:12, while Sammy Korir, the Amsterdam 
Marathon winner the past two years, has a best of 2:08:02. 
</P>
<P>
	Those four will wear starting bids 1, 2, 3 and 5. No. 4 also  
belonged to a Kenyan, Ondoro Osoro, the world's top-ranked 
marathoner last year after winning the Chicago Marathon at 2:06:54, 
the third-fastest in history and the fastest-ever for a first-time 
runner. But Osoro withdrew because of a hip injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Kagwe said this year's run is not a Kenyan lock.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want it to look like only Kenyans can win,'' Kagwe  
said. ``I don't want to say that Kenyans are super, that they can't 
be beaten. Anyone can be a winner if he prepares himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kenyans think like me. When they go into a race, they don't  
count themselves as a winner. They go in like they're a contestant. 
What we can say about Kenya is that we have a lot of big-name 
runners, like me, who are known throughout the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Known as winners, as they have been here since 1991.  
</P>
<P>
	That was the year Ibrahim Hussein won the second of his three  
titles (he was the first Kenyan winner in 1988), and his countrymen 
haven't lost since. 
</P>
<P>
	Hussein won again in 1992. Then Cosmas Ndeti won from 1993-95.  
In between Tanui's two victories, Lameck Aguta won in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	In each of the past four races, Kenyans finished at least 1-2,  
taking the first five places and seven of the top eight in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	That kind of monopolization is similar to the period between  
1916 and 1925, when Americans won all nine individual Boston races 
contested, including three by Clarence DeMar (in 1918, there was 
only team competition). 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Kenyans won nearly every major marathon in the United  
States -- Tanui at Boston, Kagwe at New York, Osoro at Chicago, 
Simon Bor at Los Angeles, Philip Tarus at the Rock 'n' Roll 
Marathon in San Diego and Mbarek Hussein, brother of Ibrahim, at 
Honolulu. 
</P>
<P>
	They also took the first six places and seven of the first 10 at  
San Diego, the first three at Honolulu, seconds at New York, Boston 
and Los Angeles, and three of the first five spots at Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are not only slaughtering the Americans, they are  
slaughtering everybody,'' Brantley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the Kenyan runners live and train in the United States,  
but their dominance has spread throughout the world, winning three 
marathons in Japan and one in South Africa last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kenyans' superiority in such a relatively short time is  
remarkable considering that not that long ago Kenyans didn't even 
run marathons. They felt it was something old men did. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, their diligent training methods are paying big dividends --  
the Boston winner gets $80,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kenyans are winning because they train hard and leave aside  
everything else, like going to discos or seeing friends at night,'' 
Tanui said. ``They only concentrate on training. They know if they 
are successful in training, they will be successful in a race. They 
go to bed at 8 o'clock and they leave (for training) at 5 in the 
morning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Korir trained between 155 and 186 miles per week during February  
to get ready for Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without training, you cannot win,'' Korir said.  
</P>
<P>
	Bobby McGee, the agent for South African Colleen de Reuck, one  
of the leading women contenders in Monday's race, said the Kenyans' 
success is due to a combination of factors. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot to be gained nationally if you can run well,''  
McGee said. ``Kenya is a poverty stricken country, so running well 
is a way to make a name for yourself instead of just being a 
number. ... 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not just a race for them. They're in it for each other.  
Ask a Kenyan if he won a race and he might say no, but he'll say a 
Kenyan did. They draw from that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGee also noted that Kenyan runners have small calf muscles and  
big thigh muscles; that they're born at altitude, so train at 
altitude; that they running in a loping, shock-absorbing way; that 
they are biomechanically sound; that ``they don't give up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only Brazilian Vanderlei Lima, Spain's Jose Garcia and Mexicans  
Andres Espinosa and Isaac Garcia are given outside chances of 
breaking the Kenyan streak. 
</P>
<P>
	Challenging Roba in the women's field are de Reuck, the road  
racer of the year in 1997; New York City Marathon champions Anuta 
Catuna of Romania, Franca Fiaconni of Italy and Franziska 
Rochat-Moser of Switzerland; two-time Olympic medalist Yuko Arimori 
of Japan; and first-time marathoners Jennings of Newmarket, N.H., 
and Catherine Ndereba of Kenya. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodgers, who also won the New York marathon four times, will try  
to break the over-50 course record of 2:31:34 for an American. 
</P>
<P>
	However, one notable will be missing -- 91-year-old Johnny  
Kelley, who finished Boston 58 times and won twice. He is 
recovering from pneumonia and colon surgery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 09:33:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hayes: Stottlemyre Had it Coming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Do not expect Charlie Hayes to be inviting Todd  
Stottlemyre to dinner anytime soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Hayes, who plays third base for the San Francisco Giants,  
charged the mound from second base Friday night with the intent of 
knocking out the Arizona Diamondbacks' pitcher. Afterward, he had 
no regrets, even if it means a suspension. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't land a punch, but I did try to hurt him,'' Hayes  
said. ``He can say `Hi' to me, and I'll try to slap him. I just 
don't like him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stottlemyre, one of the most intensely competitive players in  
baseball, has been involved in more than his share of fights in his 
12-year career as a big-league pitcher. But he said this is the 
first time anyone had gone after him from second base. 
</P>
<P>
	It happened in the sixth inning, with Arizona leading 8-3.  
Hayes, 0-for-13 lifetime against Stottlemyre, had just hit into a 
fielder's choice. Hayes moved to second on Brent Mayne's base hit, 
and Hayes and Stottlemyre continued their heated exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought he was yelling at me from first base, so when he got  
to second base, I had something to say to him,'' Stottlemyre said. 
``That was enough to trigger him, and here he came. I don't know 
why he was frustrated. I guess you'll have to ask him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hayes said his lingering feelings toward Stottlemyre added fuel  
to the exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it had been anybody else, I wouldn't have said anything,  
but I don't like him,'' Hayes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hayes rounded second and then ran full speed toward a somewhat  
startled Stottlemyre. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was trying to knock him out,'' Hayes said. ``I didn't want  
to wrestle. He talks like he's Bob Gibson. I'm the only one he can 
get out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stottlemyre ducked, and the punch failed to connect.  
</P>
<P>
	``He missed me all night at the plate and he missed me on the  
mound,'' Stottlemyre said. 
</P>
<P>
	Third baseman Matt Williams, who said he'd never seen a player  
charge the mound from second, raced to Stottlemyre's defense, 
tackling Hayes. Sonny Jackson, San Francisco's third base coach, 
tackled Stottlemyre. 
</P>
<P>
	Both dugouts emptied, and so did the bullpens. There was a big  
pile of humanity the umpires had to pull apart. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona's Randy Johnson, towering over the throng, lost his cap  
and put on Jackson's Giants' cap instead. He thought it felt a 
little snug. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess I was a Giant for a half-minute,'' Johnson said.  
</P>
<P>
	Hayes was still livid and had to be restrained by teammate Barry  
Bonds, who wrapped his arm around Hayes and walked him to the 
dugout. Stottlemyre was tossed, too, although he argued he was only 
defending himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Hayes knows he could face punishment from the league.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't care,'' Hayes said. ``I'm sick of people like that.  
Who does he think he is, Sandy Koufax or somebody? To me he's a 
.500 pitcher, 12-and-12. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think nobody likes him. I don't think some of his  
teammates like him. He's going to get some of them hurt. He needs 
to just pitch and just shut up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona manager Buck Showalter defended Stottlemyre as a fierce  
competitor, the type of player sorely needed by a second-year 
franchise trying to make a quick leap into contention in the NL 
West. 
</P>
<P>
	``I enjoyed competing against him. I always respected his  
competitive skills,'' Showalter said. ``I don't think you ever 
dislike him from the other side unless you don't like 
competitors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks lead the majors in dugout-clearing incidents in  
the early season. They had one in the second game of the season at 
Dodger Stadium when Williams angrily accused Chan Ho Park of 
throwing at his head. 
</P>
<P>
	Travis Lee, Arizona's 23-year-old first baseman, is appreciating  
the competitiveness of the Diamondbacks, whose roster is loaded 
with veteran major leaguers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a lot of gamers. They aren't going to put up with  
that,'' Lee said. ``This year we know we have a really good chance 
of winning, and sparks are going to start flying. It's great. It's 
fun.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 14:52:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dozens Hurt in Blast in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- An explosion fired nails through a crowded street  
market in south London on Saturday, injuring dozens. Witnesses said 
the blast was caused by a bomb. 
</P>
<P>
	No deaths were reported, but Scotland Yard said people had been  
seriously injured in the explosion at 5:25 p.m. local time. 
</P>
<P>
	A trader at the market said he had seen the device before it  
exploded. He said nails were stuck on it with transparent tape. 
</P>
<P>
	Commander Hugh Orde, Metropolitan Police head of crime for  
southwest London, said police received reports of at least 48 
people injured, although apparently not all sought hospital 
treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Seventeen people were admitted with ``shrapnel-type'' injuries  
at King's College Hospital, said spokesman Nick Samuels. Twelve 
people were taken to St. George's Hospital, and eight others were 
treated at St. Thomas's Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``The injuries are relatively minor, but they range from people  
who were shaken because they were blown off their feet by the blast 
to a female who had got a nail in her belly,'' said Jenny Reid, 
spokeswoman for St. Thomas's Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Police did not immediately confirm the cause of the explosion,  
and there were no reports of anyone claiming responsibility. Press 
Association, the British news agency, said police sources suggested 
the explosion was related to criminal activity and not to 
politically motivated terrorism. 
</P>
<P>
	George Jones, 42, who has a stall at the street market, said he  
had seen the device before it exploded. 
</P>
<P>
	A utility bag ``was handed to me by somebody who said someone  
had forgotten their shopping. I unzipped it and opened it wide, and 
I could see what it was,'' said Jones, who described it as being 
wrapped with tape and nails. ``I picked it up and moved it 10 to 15 
yards and put it by a brick wall to stop people getting hurt .... 
Then it went off. I was blown across the road and a couple of nails 
lodged in my leg, and I was hit by concrete and glass.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones said he had telephoned police before the explosion.  
</P>
<P>
	Neall Whatley, 36, said he saw a child with a nail in her cheek  
and an adult man with serious head, chest and leg injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``The small child, I would say, was about seven. She was just  
very, very shocked,'' Whatley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Metin Saglam, 34, who runs a fast food shop on Brixton Road near  
the site of the explosion, said: ``I heard two bangs, and there 
were people running around screaming `bomb, bomb, bomb.''' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
