<DOCNO> APW19990417.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 08:24:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge OKs Naming Chiquita Source </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- A judge says a reporter can name his  
confidential source for a package of stories accusing Chiquita 
Brands International Inc. of improper dealings in Central America. 
</P>
<P>
	The reporter, Michael Gallagher, relied on voice mail messages  
for stories published last May by The Cincinnati Enquirer. The 
newspaper later renounced the articles, fired Gallagher and paid 
Chiquita more than $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallagher pleaded guilty in September to illegally intercepting  
communications and obtaining unauthorized access to Chiquita's 
computer systems. He is awaiting sentencing that could range from 
probation to 2 1/2 years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	At a court hearing last week, Gallagher identified former  
Chiquita counsel George Ventura as one of his confidential sources. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura's attorneys said Gallagher shouldn't be allowed to name  
their client at Ventura's trial because it would violate Ohio's 
``shield law,'' which allows reporters to protect sources' 
identities. 
</P>
<P>
	However Judge Ann Marie Tracey ruled Friday that Ohio law  
doesn't protect the source from being identified if the reporter 
voluntarily divulges the source's name. The judge said the shield 
law only applies when reporters assert their right to protect their 
sources. Gallagher has willingly given up that right. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura, now an attorney in Salt Lake City, has pleaded innocent  
to five counts of unlawful interception of communications and five 
counts of unauthorized access to computer systems. He could be 
sentenced to 12 1/2 years in prison if convicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 00:13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Couch Appears To Be Browns Pick </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Barring a blockbuster trade or a breakdown at  
the bargaining table, the No. 1 pick in the NFL draft will likely 
be a No. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Couch, the quarterback who wore No. 2 while setting dozens  
of passing records at Kentucky, is expected to be Cleveland's 
choice when the Browns pick first in today's draft in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Browns are returning to the league as an expansion team  
after a three-year hiatus, and indications are that they will make 
the 21-year-old Couch their quarterback of the future. 
</P>
<P>
	Couch's agent, Tom Condon, began face-to-face contract  
negotiations with Lal Heneghan, Cleveland's contract expert, in New 
York on Friday night. The two met for three hours before breaking 
for dinner and indicated they would work through the night if 
necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	According to reports Friday night, if the two sides come to an  
agreement, the Browns will make Couch their top pick. Condon is 
reportedly seeking an 8 percent increase on the six-year, $48 
million deal he got for Peyton Manning last year when he was taken 
No. 1 by Indianapolis. He is also looking for a larger signing 
bonus than the $12 million Manning got. 
</P>
<P>
	As they prepared for the draft, the Browns received a new offer  
Friday from another team interested in moving up into the No. 1 
spot. Team president Carmen Policy would not name the team or say 
if it was the New Orleans Saints, who have already offered 
Cleveland all their picks this year plus some future ones. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are some new developments with at least one other team  
wanting to trade up and take the pick,'' Policy said. ``We have 
four alternatives, and all of them are still alive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Policy denied rumors that the Browns have already decided to  
take Couch first. He said Couch, Oregon quarterback Akili Smith and 
Texas running back Ricky Williams are all still in the mix and that 
negotiations with all three players' agents were taking place. 
</P>
<P>
	But by Friday night, Couch was the only one the Browns were  
still talking to. 
</P>
<P>
	If Cleveland is unable to sign the Kentucky quarterback, its  
second option would be to take Smith, who has the stronger arm of 
the two and appeared to be Browns coach Chris Palmer's favorite 
after a private workout last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith's agent, Leigh Steinberg, said from New York that he spoke  
with Browns' officials several times Friday and was assured his 
client was still being considered. 
</P>
<P>
	One advantage for Smith could be Steinberg's experience with  
Policy at the bargaining table. Steinberg represented several San 
Francisco 49ers, including quarterback Steve Young, whose contract 
he negotiated when Policy was 49ers president. 
</P>
<P>
	Steinberg, too, was impressed by the Browns' ability to keep  
everyone guessing. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the Cleveland Browns had been given the atomic nuclear  
secret, we would still have it,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 06:01:02 </DATE_TIME>
