<DOCNO> APW19990417.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 02:11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Pays $3.77 Million in Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Gov. George W. Bush said he and his wife  
paid $3.77 million in federal income taxes on an estimated 1998 
income of $18.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wrote a check that is the biggest check I could conceivably  
(write),'' Bush, a possible Republican candidate for the 2000 
presidential election, said Thursday. ``I never dreamt I'd write a 
check that big. Of course, I never dreamt I'd make that much money, 
either.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bushes previously paid $97,252 in taxes.  
</P>
<P>
	The bulk of Bush's 1998 income came from the sale of the Texas  
Rangers baseball team, of which he'd been managing partner before 
his 1994 election as governor. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, who bought into the Rangers for just more than $600,000,  
received about $14.9 million when sale of the club was announced 
last summer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bushes also reported giving $334,425 to churches and  
charitable organizations during 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The blind trust that manages Bush's assets has applied for an  
extension of time to file the governor's 1998 tax returns. It is 
still waiting for tax information from some entities in the trust, 
spokeswoman Karen Hughes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, who established a presidential exploratory campaign on  
March 2, has raised $7.6 million for a possible campaign so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 08:13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> D.C. Spruces Up for NATO Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An army of civil servants, corporate  
volunteers, federal planners and law enforcement officers is 
mobilizing to help the nation's capital prepare as host of its 
largest gathering of world leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the North Atlantic Treaty Organization returns for  
three days to the city where President Truman and the leaders of a 
handful of other nations created NATO in 1949. The now-19 NATO 
nations will be joined by officials from 25 eastern and central 
European partner countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an opportunity to showcase Washington, D.C. as a  
beautiful city,'' said Mayor Anthony Williams. ``We're also the 
co-host with the president and the first lady.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The event, with some 40 heads of government, 2,500 to 3,000  
media and 1,700 dignitaries, is a huge logistical challenge, said 
Dana Shelley, spokeswoman for the NATO 50th Summit Host Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor has ordered a massive cleanup of areas of the city  
that don't normally appear on postcards. Vacant lots are being 
fenced, graffiti wiped out, trees trimmed and streets swept. 
</P>
<P>
	Plans call for foreign delegations to arrive at Ronald Reagan  
National and Dulles airports in Virginia and the 
Baltimore-Washington International Airport and Andrews Air Force 
Base in Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	``That means cleaning our gateways - Georgia Avenue, New York  
Avenue - the ways that people come into our city, and then cleaning 
the neighborhoods around them,'' said Kay McGrath, a special 
assistant to the mayor. ``What one weekend does is, it helps you 
reposition the District of Columbia into its rightful position as 
the capital of the free world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	City officials see it as a prime opportunity to market  
Washington's prestige addresses -- the Capitol Hill area, portions 
of New York and Pennsylvania avenues -- in a continuing effort to 
spur economic revitalization. 
</P>
<P>
	Seventeen law enforcement agencies, including the Secret  
Service, FBI, Metropolitan Police Department and National Park 
Service Police, will provide security. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers will be prepared for unrest. ``It would be  
un-American not to have at least some demonstrators,'' said Richard 
Socarides, chief operating officer for summit organizers, 
explaining that a specific area will be designated for protesters 
granted permits. 
</P>
<P>
	Except for areas where summit events are planned, streets will  
be open and vendors will be allowed to remain, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will have rolling street closures,'' as motorcades for the  
40 heads of state move through, said Cmdr. Michael Radzilowski, 
head of the city police department's Special Operations Division. 
</P>
<P>
	``Washington, D.C. is a tough town for traffic anyway, and  
moving these folks around is a tough task for us,'' said Maj. 
General Joseph Garrett, the vice director of the NATO summit 
planning staff. 
</P>
<P>
	Soldiers from Fort Eustis, Va., are being brought in to drive  
shuttle buses and cars for dignitaries. In addition, most 
government offices near summit sites will be closed Friday to 
reduce traffic. About half the 180,000 area federal employees and 
7,500 district government workers will receive the day off with 
pay. 
</P>
<P>
	The region's subway will travel through, but not stop, at the  
Federal Triangle subway stop near the main summit site, the Ronald 
Reagan International Trade Center downtown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 11:52:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gretzky Gets Chair, Baseball Pass </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RYE, N.Y. (AP) -- Wayne Gretzky doesn't expect to sit around in  
retirement, but when he does, his New York Rangers teammates made 
sure he will be comfortable. 
</P>
<P>
	Just before their final practice together, they presented  
Gretzky with a big baseball glove chair that he had admired after 
seeing a similar one in Yankees owner George Steinbrenner's office. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't expecting any gifts, but this was great,'' said  
Gretzky. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the chair, Gretzky received a lifetime pass to  
major league baseball from the sport's chief operating officer, 
Paul Beeston. 
</P>
<P>
	As practice wound down, Rangers coach John Muckler jokingly  
suggested that Gretzky do extra down and backs exercise to stay in 
shape. The 38-year-old Gretzky laughed and declined but offered to 
lead the team in their final stretching exercises and all his 
teammates banged their sticks on the ice in salute. 
</P>
<P>
	After the exercise, winger Kevin Stevens suggested that the team  
gather for a photo dressed in their red and blue Statue of Liberty 
practice jerseys. 
</P>
<P>
	``I definitely want one final team picture tomorrow, with all of  
us in our game uniforms,'' said Gretzky. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told all the young guys to enjoy (tomorrow's game),'' said  
Gretzky. ``This is what it feels like to be in the Stanley Cup 
finals. This is how exciting it can be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many friends and family will be flying in to watch Gretzky's  
final game Sunday when the Rangers play the Pittsburgh Penguins at 
Madison Square Garden, including former Rangers and Edmonton Oilers 
teammate Mark Messier. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would love to score tomorrow,'' said Gretzky. ``But if I get  
a hat-trick I'm not going to stay, and if I don't score it's not 
going to kill me either.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
