<DOCNO> APW19990417.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 01:42:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Faulk Traded To Avoid Disruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Bill Polian traded Marshall Faulk because he  
believed the three-time Pro running back was going to demand a new 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Faulk was sent to St. Louis in exchange for the Rams' second-  
and fifth-round picks in this weekend's draft. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colts have the fourth pick in today's NFL draft and it was  
expected that Heisman Trophy winner Ricky Williams could still be 
available when Indianapolis selected. 
</P>
<P>
	``Faulk was a great player. You need to replace that. We don't  
have that now. How we go about that remains to be seen,'' Bill 
Polian said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The running back had two more years on the contract he signed as  
the No. 2 overall draft pick in 1994, and Polian said he was to be 
paid $2.9 million this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Polian, hired as the club president in December 1997 to rebuild  
a team that compiled a 3-13 mark that year, said he became 
convinced in March ``that Marshall and his agent were quite serious 
about not coming in without a new contract.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Once it was determined that a trade was in the best interests of  
the Colts, Polian said he heard from several teams and considered 
the offer by the Rams as the best deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we gave Marshall his (new contract) money, we would be  
capitulating to a holdout. We cannot do that,'' Polian said. ``I 
don't want to make this personal, but you assume that any player 
had one good year, that we should tear up his contract and 
renegotiate. 
</P>
<P>
	``We paid a hefty signing bonus to get that contract, and I  
didn't see Marshall's agent knocking on the door when Marshall was 
injured and giving us back any money. If we should have given him 
money, why didn't they give us something back when he was hurt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Colts will hold a mini-camp next week and Polian said the  
collective bargaining agreement would have resulted in a $5,000 per 
day fine if Faulk did not participate. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no point in levying those fines if they're going to be  
rescinded or forgiven ... As a result you have an atmosphere that 
isn't conducive to good feeling,'' Polian said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Polian said a holdout by Faulk ``would have been  
very damaging to our team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Polian declined to confirm that the Colts would draft Williams  
today if he was available when it is the Colts' turn to draft. He 
also said he had no plans to move up in the draft to get the former 
Texas star and that he feels no pressure to use the first-round 
pick to select a running back. 
</P>
<P>
	But, Polian said he had no problem over the prospect of having a  
rookie running back playing in a backfield with second-year 
quarterback Peyton Manning. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rookies can play running back faster than rookies can play  
most any other position,'' he said. ``Don't read anything into 
that. What they do at the college level by and large is relatively 
easier to translate to the NFL as opposed to other positions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams comes to the NFL as college football's all-time rushing  
leader, a record he set by remaining at Texas for his senior year. 
</P>
<P>
	Polian said he believes the second pick in the draft, held by  
Philadelphia, will dictate what the Colts and the other teams 
holding one of the first 10 picks will do on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stay tuned, we'll find out,'' he said. ``I anticipate that the  
phone will be ringing and we'll evaluate. We evaluate every 
different scenario.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
