<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- The Roman Catholic Church in  
Brazil appears set to mark the 500th anniversary of the nation's 
discovery next year by apologizing for its links with slavery. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil's 280 bishops met Saturday in Sao Paulo state to discuss  
the church's yearlong anniversary program, which is due to end with 
a visit by Pope John Paul II in April 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	There were indications they would decide to make a declaration  
about slavery in the program, said Maria Veiga, a spokeswoman for 
the Brazilian Bishops Council, or CNBB. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 4 million slaves were shipped from Africa to Brazil  
from 1500 until the late 19th century. Churchmen openly accepted 
slavery and kept slaves themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	The president of the CNBB, Bishop Jaime Chemello, was quoted  
this week saying that it would not be ``going too far'' to 
apologize for the church's links with slavery. 
</P>
<P>
	The church program is to be approved by the bishops before the  
annual nine-day conference ends Friday, said Veiga. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Thousands of demonstrators marched  
through Brazilian cities on Saturday to protest the alleged 
massacre of 19 peasants by police in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Next week, a trial date is expected for 154 police officers  
accused of carrying out the killings at a land rights march in 
Eldorado de Carajas in the northern state of Para. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, the massacre's third anniversary, more than 5,000  
people marched in Salvador, capital of the northeastern state of 
Bahia, and hundreds more did so in Sao Paulo. 
</P>
<P>
	Marches were scheduled in other state capitals Sunday and  
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The marches were being led by the Landless Rural Workers  
Movement, which has gained national prominence for invading 
uncultivated land to speed up the government's land reform program. 
</P>
<P>
	About 20 percent of Brazil's population owns 88 percent of the  
land, while the poorest 40 percent owns just 1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- Portugal and Brazil on Saturday urged  
the European Union to provide a clear mandate for negotiations on a 
free trade agreement with Latin American nations grouped in the 
Mercosur trading bloc. 
</P>
<P>
	``Europe must understand that it is strategic for its global  
position to deepen relations with Mercosur,'' Portuguese Prime 
Minister Antonio Guterres said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso called on the EU  
to reach a trading agreement as soon as possible with Mercosur -- 
composed of Brazil, Argentina, Uruguay and Paraguay. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardoso was due to leave Lisbon for London on Sunday, after a  
three-day visit to attend a summit focusing on cultural and 
economic ties between Portugal and its former colony. 
</P>
<P>
	Guterres said EU-Mercosur trade talks should ``have the  
potential for significant advances in reaching understanding on 
items like agriculture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Agriculture is a particular sticking point as Mercosur complains  
that EU countries spend up to $160 billion per year to subsidize 
European producers. 
</P>
<P>
	Mercosur says that while its imports from Europe have  
skyrocketed in recent years exports to Europe have increased much 
more slowly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
