<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Botched Launch Probe Delays NASA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- NASA's $1.5 billion Chandra X-ray  
telescope may have to remain on Earth a while longer due to an 
investigation into a stranded military satellite. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force has impounded an upper-stage motor intended for  
the telescope, to be launched in July aboard space shuttle 
Columbia. It's the same kind of motor that apparently malfunctioned 
April 9 and left the Defense Department's newest Defense Support 
Program satellite in a useless orbit. 
</P>
<P>
	The telescope-delivery mission already is a year late because of  
bad circuit boards that had to be replaced in Chandra and other 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``This telescope is a multibillion-dollar investment. You can  
rest assured the program is not going to go launch it until all the 
open questions have been answered,'' said payload manager Scott 
Higginbotham. 
</P>
<P>
	The stranded military satellite is spinning so fast in its  
lopsided orbit that Air Force controllers have yet to unfurl its 
electricity-generating solar panels. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're continually trying to work with it,'' Staff Sgt. Steve  
Horton of Schriever Air Force Base in Colorado said Friday. 
``There's always a hope that they can recover it and rescue it and 
get it into its proper orbit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The $250 million satellite needs to be in a circular  
22,300-mile-high orbit in order to perform its missile-warning job. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Aeronautics and Space Administration is working  
with the Air Force's accident investigation board, which convened 
earlier this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force must deliver the impounded Boeing-built motor to  
NASA by the end of April if the space agency hopes to meet its July 
9 launch date for Chandra, said Higginbotham. 
</P>
<P>
	Chandra, a Hubble-caliber observatory, should have rocketed into  
orbit last summer. Unlike Hubble, the X-ray telescope will be 
placed in an orbit too high to be reached by spacewalking 
astronauts so it will be irreparable once launched. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 08:31:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Starr Won't Say When Probe Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Kenneth W. Starr is both Exhibit A and prime  
witness for an end to the independent counsel system that put him 
on President Clinton's case five years ago. But even with the law 
virtually certain to expire early this summer, Starr's operation 
won't. 
</P>
<P>
	Not until his Office of Independent Counsel concludes that its  
work is done. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr wouldn't say how long he expects that to take. An aide had  
said earlier it might be close to two years. That would make the 
Whitewater independent counsel the longest-running and costliest 
ever. 
</P>
<P>
	And perhaps the last.  
</P>
<P>
	Starr told a Senate committee considering renewal of the law  
that Congress should let it expire on June 30, at least temporarily 
``for a cooling-off period or, perhaps more aptly, a cease-fire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tempers, especially Democratic tempers, are still high after the  
Monica Lewinsky investigation and the impeachment of Clinton on 
charges brought by Starr. Clinton was acquitted by the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Just as Republican tempers flared over the independent counsel  
process in 1992, when an earlier prosecutor issued a report that 
questioned President Bush's truthfulness just before the election 
he lost to Clinton. That led Republicans to block renewal of the 
law, and it lapsed for 18 months before it was revived, with 
Clinton's backing. 
</P>
<P>
	After five years of being under Starr's scrutiny, Clinton  
opposed renewing it again, a rare point of agreement with the 
independent prosecutor he said long ago was out to get him. And 
that was before the Lewinsky case. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's position was consistent with views he'd expressed before  
his appointment as Whitewater independent counsel by a three-judge 
federal court panel. But it was startling to senators, given his 
role since. Democratic critics said he poisoned attitudes toward 
the whole system with excesses in his prosecutions, which he 
denied. 
</P>
<P>
	He defended his operation, complained about political assaults  
on it, and said he's not finished. ``We're going to enforce the 
law,'' he said. ``That's our duty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Starr said he still has the authority to seek an indictment  
of Clinton after the president leaves office. For that to be done, 
his prosecution force would have to be in operation after Jan. 20, 
2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Could be. The law provides that independent counsels on duty  
when it expires can complete their work. There are three others 
still active. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr said the independent counsel system is constitutionally,  
practically and politically flawed. ``Independent counsels are 
especially vulnerable to partisan attack,'' Starr said. ``In this 
fashion, the legislative effort to take politics out of law 
enforcement sometimes has the ironic effect of further politicizing 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He has long complained that the Clinton's defenders were trying  
to make the prosecutors the villains of the piece. ``The assaults 
took a toll,'' he said. ``A duly authorized ... investigation came 
to be characterized as yet another political game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Law becomes politics by other means.''  
</P>
<P>
	But there is a reverse side to that. The lawsuit that produced  
the Lewinsky case was grounded in politics, pressed and financed by 
Clinton's conservative foes. And Democrats complain that people in 
Starr's operation were in contact with lawyers involved in the case 
against Clinton. He insists that there were no improprieties. 
</P>
<P>
	In a case as sensitive as one against the president, even the  
appearance of anything out of line invites political attack. 
Starr's tactics made him a target. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr put his own spin on that. He said that because an  
independent counsel is vulnerable to partisan attack, ``the 
investigation is likely to be seen as political.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That being so, he said, better to put the responsibility for it  
all where tradition assigns it, on the attorney general as 
prosecutor and on Congress as overseer. 
</P>
<P>
	It worked that way until 1978, when the Independent Counsel Act  
was created, an outgrowth of Watergate. Until then, when there were 
outside prosecutors -- and there were only five -- they were chosen 
by attorneys general, seldom because they wanted to but because 
they had to. 
</P>
<P>
	In President Nixon's case, a special prosecutor was the price  
for confirmation of his attorney general. When Nixon fired one, the 
political storm forced him to accept another, and he was on his way 
out of the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Political pressure drove Clinton to have the first outside  
prosecutor in Whitewater appointed to the job Starr took over when 
the counsel law was re-enacted in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	When the two-party system is working, there's always going to be  
somebody to blow the whistle on alleged corruption. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr again:  
</P>
<P>
	``Returning the authority over these prosecutions to attorneys  
general, and relying on them to appoint outside counsel when 
necessary, is the worst system -- except for all the others.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist  
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national 
politics for more than 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	 *End adv for Sunday, April 18, and thereafter    	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
