<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 20:13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Hitting Yugoslav Targets  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- In the 25th night of NATO bombing, a  
major oil refinery in Yugoslavia's second largest city was bombed, 
and Yugoslav officials say a 3-year-old girl was killed in attacks 
near Belgrade. Serb television described the bombing as the 
strongest attack so far of the air campaign. Targets also were hit 
around Belgrade. Serb authorities said the 3-year-old was killed 
and five people were injured in an attack in Batajnica, about 12 
miles north of Belgrade, where a military airfield is located. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Trading of POWs Unlikely  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- There is little chance of a prisoner exchange  
between the United States and Yugoslavia, officials said today. 
While U.S. military leaders are mulling what to do with a captured 
Yugoslav lieutenant, they remain aware of the three American 
soldiers seized near the Macedonian border two weeks ago. Trading 
the captured officer would be a politically tricky equation, 
officials said. On one hand, release of the three Americans would 
be a relief, but it would carry the risk of equating what the 
United States calls an abduction of peacekeeping soldiers with the 
capture of a bona fide enemy POW. 

</P>
<P>
	Castro May Spare Convicted Bombers  
</P>
<P>
	SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) -- Cuban leader Fidel  
Castro has promised to consider sparing the lives of two 
Salvadorans sentenced to death for terrorism in Cuba, El Salvador's 
president said today. President Armando Calderon Sol said he asked 
Castro for clemency on behalf of the men's families and ``in the 
name of the Salvadoran people.'' Calderon Sol noted that the men's 
cases were now before Cuba's Supreme Tribunal and later could be 
referred to the Council of State, over which Castro presides. Otto 
Rene Rodriguez Llerena and Ernesto Cruz Leon were convicted in 
March of terrorism charges and sentenced to death. 

</P>
<P>
	Dozens Injured in London Blast  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- A bomb fired nails through a crowded street market  
in south London today, injuring at least 48 people, police said. No 
one was killed, but Scotland Yard said four people had been 
seriously injured in the explosion at 5:25 p.m. local time. 
``Clearly the person who set this off is disturbed and had no 
regard for human life,'' said Commander Hugh Orde, the Metropolitan 
Police officer leading the investigation. There was no report of 
anyone claiming responsibility. 

</P>
<P>
	Poll Says Gore Hurt by Clinton  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Public weariness over the Clinton  
administration's ethical problems could hurt Vice President Al 
Gore's chances of winning the presidency in 2000, a new poll is 
indicating. For the first time since September 1997, when Gore was 
at the center of a controversy about campaign fund-raising, his 
favorable ratings slipped below 50 percent in the poll by the Pew 
Research Center for the People &AMP; the Press. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Destroyer Named for Churchill  
</P>
<P>
	BATH, Maine (AP) -- A U.S. Navy destroyer was launched today  
bearing the name of former British prime minister Sir Winston 
Churchill -- an honor rarely afforded foreigners. Lady Soames, the 
former British leader's only living child, joined U.S. Defense 
Secretary William Cohen, British Defense Minister George Robertson 
and other Churchill relatives to watch the 505-foot warship Winston 
S. Churchill slide down a greased ramp at the Bath Iron Works into 
the Kennebec River. 

</P>
<P>
	Top Three NFL Picks Are QBs  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Tim Couch, Donovan McNabb and Akili Smith went  
1-2-3 to Cleveland, Philadelphia and Cincinnati in today's NFL 
draft -- the first quarterback trifecta since 1971. And five QBs 
overall were taken in the top dozen with Daunte Culpepper going to 
Minnesota with the 11th pick and Cade McNown to Chicago with the 
next choice. The New Orleans Saints, meanwhile, traded all of their 
1999 draft picks plus next year's No. 1 and No. 3 choices to the 
Washington Redskins so they could select Heisman Trophy-winning 
running back Ricky Williams with the fifth overall selection. 

</P>
<P>
	Hurricanes Tie Senators, 1-1  
</P>
<P>
	GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) -- Bates Battaglia's second-period goal  
gave the Carolina Hurricanes a 1-1 tie with Ottawa tonight, 
eliminating the Senators from the top playoff seed in the Eastern 
Conference. Ottawa needed a win against Carolina and a New Jersey 
loss to secure the No. 1 spot in the conference, but the Hurricanes 
were able to produce their franchise-record 24th tie of the season. 
Carolina finished 1-5-18 in those games. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
</TEXT>
