<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Federal Trial Wins Hialeah Turf Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HIALEAH, Fla. (AP) -- Federal Trial took the lead turning for  
home and beat Sharp Appeal by 1 1/4 lengths Saturday in the Grade II 
$200,000 Hialeah Turf Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Long shot Karmiyan held on for third in front of Panama City,  
the 8-5 favorite, in the 1 3-16 mile turf race for 3-year-olds and 
up. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner, ridden by Robbie Davis, was timed in 1:51 3-5 and  
paid $6.60, $3.60 and $3.40. Sharp Appeal, who won the Turf Cup two 
years ago, paid $4 and $3.40, while Karamiyan paid $6.80 to show. 
</P>
<P>
	After finishing fourth in his debut last June 26, Federal Trial  
has won six of eight starts with two seconds and earned $268,990. 
The 4-year-old son of Skip Trial is a homebred owned by Arthur 
Appleton. 
</P>
<P>
	At the top of the stretch, Federal Trial took the lead by a neck  
over Auroral. In midstretch, Sharp Appeal moved to challenge from 
the outside and was within a half-length of Federal Appeal at the 
sixteenth pole. 
</P>
<P>
	In the final 70 yards, Federal Trial proved decisively best.  
Karamiyan was two lengths behind Sharp Appeal and a head in front 
of Panama City. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990417.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 00:31:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gretzky Ends a Magnificent Career </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Wayne Gretzky kept his emotions in check while  
announcing his retirement. The hard part will come Sunday when he 
takes off his skates for the last time following the New York 
Rangers' game with the Pittsburgh Penguins at Madison Square 
Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	``That will be a tough time,'' the 38-year-old Gretzky said.  
``I've played for 35 years ... since I was 3. Now I'm handing in my 
skates. I'm done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gretzky remained composed Friday as he announced he was leaving  
the game he loved following several months of agonized 
self-searching. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a gut feeling, something I really believe is right,''  
said the NHL's all-time leading scorer and No. 1 goodwill 
ambassador. ``I have peace of mind. A farewell season was not on my 
agenda.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gretzky referred to a recent request by NHL commissioner Gary  
Bettman that the Great One play one more year and make it a virtual 
farewell tour of the league, similar to what big stars have done in 
other sports. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't feel it was the right thing for me to do,'' Gretzky  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's press conference was easily one of the biggest in team  
history. Hundreds of media from print, radio and television were in 
attendance to record the end of an era. 
</P>
<P>
	Gretzky sat on a dais with his wife, Janet, and two of their  
children, Ty and Trevor. Gretzky said his daughter, Paulina, did 
not want to come ``because she thought she'd cry too much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also in attendance were Bettman, Rangers coach John Muckler, GM  
Neil Smith and Charles Dolan, head of Cablevision, which owns the 
Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	In his introductory words, Bettman said that ``all fans of  
hockey were sad.'' Most of the others on the dais looked as if they 
were at a funeral, but not Gretzky. He remained upbeat throughout 
his announcement and later when taking questions from the media. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me, it's a party, a celebration,'' Gretzky said of his  
final weekend in hockey. ``It's going to be a lot of fun. I'm not 
thinking of this as a downer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gretzky seemed like a man very much at peace with himself,  
particularly after finalizing his decision about retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew for five days I had made the right decision,'' said  
Gretzky, who revealed that his thought process about retirement had 
started as far back as Christmas. 
</P>
<P>
	Just about everyone tried to change Gretzky's mind, including  
his wife and the prime minister of Canada. Dolan made a last-ditch 
effort on Friday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a nice conversation,'' Gretzky said. ``He extended a  
hand out to me to stay with the team. I told him I hadn't wavered 
at all. I'm very confident about that now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gretzky's departure marks the second time in three months that  
one of the world's premier athletes -- and the best in his sport -- 
has chosen retirement. But unlike Michael Jordan, who left after 
winning his sixth NBA championship, Gretzky ends his career with a 
disappointing Rangers team that didn't make the playoffs this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody wants to go out like Michael Jordan did, but it's  
not a perfect world. ... It's not going to happen that way, not 
this year, but it is nice to be able to say people do want me to 
play more,'' Gretzky had said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan, and now Gretzky's departure, certainly has made 1999 a  
year for losing sports heroes. Then there's the Yankee Clipper, Joe 
DiMaggio, who died last month at age 84. 
</P>
<P>
	Ultimately, Gretzky decided to leave sooner rather than later  
following a troubled season that included a neck injury and the 
Rangers' failure to make the playoffs for the second straight year. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's going to leave a big void,'' longtime friend and Hall of  
Famer Gordie Howe said from his winter home in Florida. ``He's a 
proud man. And when you're hurting, it makes you think.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1,486 games with teams in Edmonton, Los Angeles, St. Louis  
and New York, Gretzky has 894 goals and 1,962 assists for 2,856 
points -- 1,006 more than runner-up Howe scored in his Hall of Fame 
career. 
</P>
<P>
	Gretzky owns roughly 60 records, is a 10-time scoring champion  
and a nine-time MVP. But the 1998-99 season was one of frustration 
for Gretzky as he struggled through his injury problems and said he 
was ``feeling more fatigue than I ever felt before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that he saw some declines in his talents,'' Muckler  
said. ``Wayne's a very proud person and he wanted to go out on his 
own terms. Maybe he felt that if he didn't do it now, he wouldn't 
be able to do that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
